07Jdg 1:1 After the death of Joshua, the Israelites inquired of the LORD, "Who will be the first to fight for us against the Canaanites?"
07Jdg 1:2 The LORD answered, "Judah is to go. I have handed the land over to him."
07Jdg 1:3 Judah said to his brother Simeon, "Come with me to my territory, and let us fight against the Canaanites. I will also go with you to your territory." So Simeon went with him.
07Jdg 1:4 When Judah attacked, the LORD handed the Canaanites and Perizzites over to them. They struck down 10,000 men in Bezek.
07Jdg 1:5 They found Adoni-bezek in Bezek, fought against him, and struck down the Canaanites and Perizzites.
07Jdg 1:6 When Adoni-bezek fled, they pursued him, seized him, and cut off his thumbs and big toes.
07Jdg 1:7 Adoni-bezek said, "Seventy kings with their thumbs and big toes cut off used to pick up [scraps] under my table. God has repaid me for what I have done." They brought him to Jerusalem, and he died there.
07Jdg 1:8 The men of Judah fought against Jerusalem and captured it. They put the city to the sword and set it on fire.
07Jdg 1:9 Afterwards, the men of Judah marched down to fight against the Canaanites who were living in the hill country, the Negev, and the Judean foothills.
07Jdg 1:10 Judah also marched against the Canaanites who were living in Hebron (Hebron was formerly named Kiriath-arba). They struck down Sheshai, Ahiman, and Talmai.
07Jdg 1:11 From there they marched against the residents of Debir (Debir was formerly named Kiriath-sepher).
07Jdg 1:12 Caleb said, "Whoever strikes down and captures Kiriath-sepher, I will give my daughter Achsah to him as a wife."
07Jdg 1:13 So Othniel son of Kenaz, Caleb's youngest brother, captured it, and Caleb gave his daughter Achsah to him as his wife.
07Jdg 1:14 When she arrived, she persuaded Othniel to ask her father for a field. As she got off her donkey, Caleb asked her, "What do you want?"
07Jdg 1:15 She answered him, "Give me a blessing. Since you have given me land in the Negev, give me springs of water also." So Caleb gave her both the upper and lower springs.
07Jdg 1:16 The descendants of the Kenite, Moses' father-in-law, had gone up with the men of Judah from the City of Palms to the Wilderness of Judah, which was in the Negev of Arad. They went to live among the people.
07Jdg 1:17 Judah went with his brother Simeon, struck the Canaanites who were living in Zephath, and completely destroyed the town. So they named the town Hormah.
07Jdg 1:18 Judah captured Gaza and its territory, Ashkelon and its territory, and Ekron and its territory.
07Jdg 1:19 The LORD was with Judah and enabled them to take possession of the hill country, but they could not drive out the people who were living in the valley because those people had iron chariots.
07Jdg 1:20 Judah gave Hebron to Caleb, just as Moses had promised. Then Caleb drove out the three sons of Anak who lived there.
07Jdg 1:21 At the same time the Benjaminites did not drive out the Jebusites who were living in Jerusalem. The Jebusites have lived among the Benjaminites in Jerusalem to this day.
07Jdg 1:22 The house of Joseph also attacked Bethel, and the LORD was with them.
07Jdg 1:23 They sent spies to Bethel (the town was formerly named Luz).
07Jdg 1:24 The spies saw a man coming out of the town and said to him, "Please show us how to get into town, and we will treat you well."
07Jdg 1:25 When he showed them the way into the town, they put the town to the sword but released the man and his entire family.
07Jdg 1:26 Then the man went to the land of the Hittites, built a town, and named it Luz. That is its name to this day.
07Jdg 1:27 At that time Manasseh failed to take possession of Beth-sheanand its villages, or Taanach and its villages, or the residents of Dor and its villages, or the residents of Ibleamand its villages, or the residents of Megiddo and its villages. But the Canaanites refused to leave this land.
07Jdg 1:28 When Israel became stronger, they made the Canaanites serve as forced labor but never drove them out completely.
07Jdg 1:29 At that time Ephraim failed to drive out the Canaanites who were living in Gezer, so the Canaanites have lived among them in Gezer.
07Jdg 1:30 Zebulun failed to drive out the residents of Kitron or the residents of Nahalol, so the Canaanites lived among them and served as forced labor.
07Jdg 1:31 Asher failed to drive out the residents of Acco or of Sidon, or Ahlab, Achzib, Helbah, Aphik, or Rehob.
07Jdg 1:32 The Asherites lived among the Canaanites who were living in the land, because they failed to drive them out.
07Jdg 1:33 Naphtali did not drive out the residents of Beth-shemesh or the residents of Beth-anath. They lived among the Canaanites who were living in the land, but the residents of Beth-shemesh and Beth-anath served as their forced labor.
07Jdg 1:34 The Amorites forced the Danites into the hill country and did not allow them to go down into the valley.
07Jdg 1:35 The Amorites refused to leave Har-heres, Aijalon, and Shaalbim. When the house of Joseph got the upper hand, the Amorites were made to serve as forced labor.
07Jdg 1:36 The territory of the Amorites extended from the ascent of Akrabbim, that is from Sela upward.
07Jdg 2:1 The Angel of the LORD went up from Gilgal to Bochim and said, "I brought you out of Egypt and led you into the land I had promised to your fathers. I also said: I will never break My covenant with you.
07Jdg 2:2 You are not to make a covenant with the people who are living in this land, and you are to tear down their altars.But you have not obeyed Me. What is this you have done?
07Jdg 2:3 Therefore, I now say: I will not drive out these people before you. They will be thornsin your sides, and their gods will be a trap to you."
07Jdg 2:4 When the Angel of the LORD had spoken these words to all the Israelites, the people wept loudly.
07Jdg 2:5 So they named that place Bochim and offered sacrifices there to the LORD.
07Jdg 2:6 Joshua sent the people away, and the Israelites went to take possession of the land, each to his own inheritance.
07Jdg 2:7 The people worshiped the LORD throughout Joshua's lifetime and during the lifetimes of the elders who outlived Joshua. They had seen all the LORD's great works He had done for Israel.
07Jdg 2:8 Joshua son of Nun, the servant of the Lord, died at the age of 110.
07Jdg 2:9 They buried him in the territory of his inheritance, in Timnath-heres, in the hill country of Ephraim, north of Mount Gaash.
07Jdg 2:10 That whole generation was also gathered to their ancestors. After them another generation rose up who did not know the LORD or the works He had done for Israel.
07Jdg 2:11 The Israelites did what was evil in the LORD's sight. They worshiped the Baals
07Jdg 2:12 and abandoned the LORD, the God of their fathers, who had brought them out of Egypt. They went after other gods from the surrounding peoples and bowed down to them. They infuriated the LORD,
07Jdg 2:13 for they abandoned Him and worshiped Baal and the Ashtoreths.
07Jdg 2:14 The LORD's anger burned against Israel, and He handed them over to marauders who raided them. He sold them to the enemies around them, so that they could no longer resist their enemies.
07Jdg 2:15 Whenever the Israelites went out, the LORD was against them and brought disaster [on them], just as He had promised and sworn to them. So they suffered greatly.
07Jdg 2:16 The LORD raised up judges, who saved them from the power of their marauders,
07Jdg 2:17 but they did not listen to their judges. Instead, they prostituted themselves with other gods, bowing down to them. They quickly turned from the way of their fathers, who had walked in obedience to the LORD's commands. They did not do as their fathers did.
07Jdg 2:18 Whenever the LORD raised up a judge for the Israelites, the LORD was with him and saved the people from the power of their enemies while the judge was still alive. The LORD was moved to pity whenever they groaned because of those who were oppressing and afflicting them.
07Jdg 2:19 Whenever the judge died, the Israelites would act even more corruptly than their fathers, going after other gods to worship and bow down to them. They did not turn from their [evil] practices or their obstinate ways.
07Jdg 2:20 The Lord's anger burned against Israel, and He declared, "Because this nation has violated My covenant that I made with their fathers and disobeyed Me,
07Jdg 2:21 I will no longer drive out before them any of the nations Joshua left when he died.
07Jdg 2:22 [I did this] to test Israel and to see whether they would keep the LORD's way by walking in it, as their fathers had."
07Jdg 2:23 The LORD left these nations and did not drive them out immediately. He did not hand them over to Joshua.
07Jdg 3:1 These are the nations the LORD left in order to test Israel, since none of these Israelites had fought in any of the wars with Canaan.
07Jdg 3:2 This was to teach the future generations of the Israelites [how to fight in] battle, especially those who had not fought before.
07Jdg 3:3 [These nations included:] the five rulers of the Philistines and all of the Canaanites, the Sidonians, and the Hivites who lived in the Lebanese mountains from Mount Baal-hermon as far as the entrance to Hamath.
07Jdg 3:4 The LORD left them to test Israel, to determine if they would keep the LORD's commands He had given their fathers through Moses.
07Jdg 3:5 But they settled among the Canaanites, Hittites, Amorites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites.
07Jdg 3:6 The Israelites took their daughters as wives for themselves, gave their own daughters to their sons, and worshiped their gods.
07Jdg 3:7 The Israelites did what was evil in the LORD's sight; they forgot the LORD their God and worshiped the Baals and the Asherahs.
07Jdg 3:8 The LORD's anger burned against Israel, and He sold them to Cushan-rishathaim king of Aram of the Two Rivers,and the Israelites served him eight years.
07Jdg 3:9 The Israelites cried out to the LORD. So the LORD raised up Othniel son of Kenaz, Caleb's youngest brother as a deliverer to save the Israelites.
07Jdg 3:10 The Spirit of the LORD was on him, and he judged Israel. Othniel went out to battle, and the LORD handed over Cushan-rishathaim king of Aram to him, so that Othniel overpowered him.
07Jdg 3:11 Then the land was peaceful 40 years, and Othniel son of Kenaz died.
07Jdg 3:12 The Israelites again did what was evil in the LORD's sight. He gave Eglon king of Moab power over Israel, because they had done what was evil in the LORD's sight.
07Jdg 3:13 After Eglon convinced the Ammonites and the Amalekites to join forces with him, he attacked and defeated Israel and took possession of the City of Palms.
07Jdg 3:14 The Israelites served Eglon king of Moab 18 years.
07Jdg 3:15 Then the Israelites cried out to the LORD, and He raised up Ehud son of Gera, a left-handed Benjaminite, as a deliverer for them. The Israelites sent him to Eglon king of Moab with tribute [money].
07Jdg 3:16 Ehud made himself a double-edged sword 18 inches long. He strapped it to his right thigh under his clothes
07Jdg 3:17 and brought the tribute to Eglon king of Moab, who was an extremely fat man.
07Jdg 3:18 When Ehud had finished presenting the tribute, he dismissed the people who had carried it.
07Jdg 3:19 At the carved images near Gilgal he returned and said, "King [Eglon], I have a secret message for you." The king called for silence, and all his attendants left him.
07Jdg 3:20 Then Ehud approached him while he was sitting alone in his room upstairs [where it was] cool. Ehud said, "I have a word from God for you," and the king stood up from his throne.
07Jdg 3:21 Ehud reached with his left hand, took the sword from his right thigh, and plunged it into Eglon's belly.
07Jdg 3:22 Even the handle went in after the blade, and Eglon's fat closed in over it, so that Ehud did not withdraw the sword from his belly. And Eglon's insides came out.
07Jdg 3:23 Ehud escaped by way of the porch, closing and locking the doors of the upstairs room behind him.
07Jdg 3:24 Ehud was gone when Eglon's servants came in. They looked and found the doors of the upstairs room locked and thought he was relieving himself in the cool room.
07Jdg 3:25 The servants waited until they became worried and saw that he had still not opened the doors of the upstairs room. So they took the key and opened the doors-- and there was their lord lying dead on the floor!
07Jdg 3:26 Ehud escaped while the servants waited. He crossed over [the Jordan] near the carved images and reached Seirah.
07Jdg 3:27 After he arrived, he sounded the ram's horn throughout the hill country of Ephraim. The Israelites came down with him from the hill country, and he became their leader.
07Jdg 3:28 He told them, "Follow me, because the LORD has handed over your enemies, the Moabites, to you." So they followed him, captured the fords of the Jordan leading to Moab, and did not allow anyone to cross over.
07Jdg 3:29 At that time they struck down about 10,000 Moabites, all strong and able-bodied men. Not one of them escaped.
07Jdg 3:30 Moab became subject to Israel that day, and the land was peaceful 80 years.
07Jdg 3:31 After Ehud, Shamgar son of Anath [became judge]. He delivered Israel by striking down 600 Philistines with an oxgoad.
07Jdg 4:1 The Israelites again did what was evil in the sight of the LORD after Ehud had died.
07Jdg 4:2 So the LORD sold them into the hand of Jabin king of Canaan, who reigned in Hazor. The commander of his forces was Sisera who lived in Harosheth of the Nations.
07Jdg 4:3 Then the Israelites cried out to the LORD, because Jabin had 900 iron chariots, and he harshly oppressed them 20 years.
07Jdg 4:4 Deborah, a woman who was a prophet and the wife of Lappidoth, was judging Israel at that time.
07Jdg 4:5 It was her custom to sit under the palm tree of Deborah between Ramah and Bethel in the hill country of Ephraim, and the Israelites went up to her for judgment.
07Jdg 4:6 She summoned Barak son of Abinoam from Kedesh in Naphtali and said to him, "Hasn't the LORD, the God of Israel, commanded [you]: 'Go, deploy [the troops] on Mount Tabor, and take with you 10,000 men from the Naphtalites and Zebulunites?
07Jdg 4:7 Then I will lure Sisera commander of Jabin's forces, his chariots, and his army at the Wadi Kishon [to fight] against you, and I will hand him over to you.'"
07Jdg 4:8 Barak said to her, "If you will go with me, I will go. But if you will not go with me, I will not go."
07Jdg 4:9 "I will go with you," she said, "but you will receive no honor on the road you are about to take, because the LORD will sell Sisera into a woman's hand." So Deborah got up and went with Barak to Kedesh.
07Jdg 4:10 Barak summoned Zebulun and Naphtali to Kedesh; 10,000 men followed him, and Deborah also went with him.
07Jdg 4:11 Now Heber the Kenite had moved away from the Kenites, the sons of Hobab, Moses' father-in-law, and pitched his tent beside the oak tree of Zaanannim, which was near Kedesh.
07Jdg 4:12 It was reported to Sisera that Barak son of Abinoam had gone up Mount Tabor.
07Jdg 4:13 Sisera summoned all his 900 iron chariots and all the people who were with him from Harosheth of the Nations to the Wadi Kishon.
07Jdg 4:14 Then Deborah said to Barak, "Move on, for this is the day the LORD has handed Sisera over to you. Hasn't the LORD gone before you?" So Barak came down from Mount Tabor with 10,000 men following him.
07Jdg 4:15 The LORD threw Sisera, all his charioteers, and all his army into confusion with the sword before Barak. Sisera left his chariot and fled on foot.
07Jdg 4:16 Barak pursued the chariots and the army as far as Harosheth of the Nations, and the whole army of Sisera fell by the sword; not a single man was left.
07Jdg 4:17 Meanwhile, Sisera had fled on foot to the tent of Jael, the wife of Heber the Kenite, because there was peace between Jabin king of Hazor and the family of Heber the Kenite.
07Jdg 4:18 Jael went out to greet Sisera and said to him, "Come in, my lord. Come in with me. Don't be afraid." So he went into her tent, and she covered him with a rug.
07Jdg 4:19 He said to her, "Please give me a little water to drink for I am thirsty." She opened a container of milk, gave him a drink, and covered him [again].
07Jdg 4:20 Then he said to her, "Stand at the entrance to the tent. If a man comes and asks you, 'Is there a man here?' say, 'No.'"
07Jdg 4:21 While he was sleeping from exhaustion, Heber's wife Jael took a tent peg, grabbed a hammer, and went silently to Sisera. She hammered the peg into his temple and drove it into the ground, and he died.
07Jdg 4:22 When Barak arrived in pursuit of Sisera, Jael went out to greet him and said to him, "Come and I will show you the man you are looking for." So he went in with her, and there was Sisera lying dead with a tent peg through his temple!
07Jdg 4:23 That day God subdued Jabin king of Canaan before the Israelites.
07Jdg 4:24 The power of the Israelites continued to increase against Jabin king of Canaan until they destroyed him.
07Jdg 5:1 On that day Deborah and Barak son of Abinoam sang:
07Jdg 5:2 When the leaders lead in Israel, when the people volunteer, praise the LORD.
07Jdg 5:3 Listen, kings! Pay attention, princes! I will sing to the LORD; I will sing praise to the LORD God of Israel.
07Jdg 5:4 LORD, when You came from Seir, when You marched from the fields of Edom, the earth trembled, the heavens poured [rain], the clouds poured water.
07Jdg 5:5 The mountains melted before the LORD, even Sinai before the LORD, the God of Israel.
07Jdg 5:6 In the days of Shamgar son of Anath, in the days of Jael, the main ways were deserted, because travelers kept to the side roads.
07Jdg 5:7 Villages were deserted, they were deserted in Israel, until I, Deborah, I arose, a mother in Israel.
07Jdg 5:8 Israel chose new gods, then war was in the gates. Not a shield or spear was seen among 40,000 in Israel.
07Jdg 5:9 My heart is with the leaders of Israel, with the volunteers of the people. Praise the LORD!
07Jdg 5:10 You who ride on white donkeys, who sit on saddle blankets, and who travel on the road, give praise!
07Jdg 5:11 Let them tell the righteous acts of the LORD, the righteous deeds of His warriors in Israel, with the voices of the singers at the watering places. Then the LORD's people went down to the gates.
07Jdg 5:12 "Awake! Awake, Deborah! Awake! Awake, sing a song! Arise Barak, and take hold of your captives, son of Abinoam!"
07Jdg 5:13 The survivors came down to the nobles; the LORD's people came down to me with the warriors.
07Jdg 5:14 Those with their roots in Amalek [came] from Ephraim; Benjamin [came with] your people after you. The leaders came down from Machir, and those who carry a marshal's staff [came] from Zebulun.
07Jdg 5:15 The princes of Issachar were with Deborah; Issachar was with Barak. They set out at his heels in the valley. There was great searching of heart among the clans of Reuben.
07Jdg 5:16 Why did you sit among the sheepfolds listening to the playing of pipes for the flocks? There was great searching of heart among the clans of Reuben.
07Jdg 5:17 Gilead remained beyond the Jordan. Dan, why did you linger at the ships? Asher remained at the seashore and stayed in his harbors.
07Jdg 5:18 Zebulun was a people risking their lives, Naphtali also, on the heights of the battlefield.
07Jdg 5:19 Kings came and fought. Then the kings of Canaan fought at Taanach by the waters of Megiddo, but they took no spoil of silver.
07Jdg 5:20 The stars fought from the heavens; the stars fought with Sisera from their courses.
07Jdg 5:21 The river Kishon swept them away, the ancient river, the river Kishon. March on, my soul, in strength!
07Jdg 5:22 The horses' hooves then hammered-- the galloping, galloping of his stallions.
07Jdg 5:23 "Curse Meroz," says the Angel of the LORD, "Bitterly curse her inhabitants, for they did not come to help the LORD, to help the LORD against the mighty warriors."
07Jdg 5:24 Jael is most blessed of women, the wife of Heber the Kenite; she is most blessed among tent-dwelling women.
07Jdg 5:25 He asked for water; she gave him milk. She brought him curdled milk in a majestic bowl.
07Jdg 5:26 She reached for a tent peg, her right hand, for a workman's mallet. Then she hammered Sisera-- she crushed his head; she shattered and pierced his temple.
07Jdg 5:27 He collapsed, he fell, he lay down at her feet; he collapsed, he fell at her feet; where he collapsed, there he fell-- dead.
07Jdg 5:28 Sisera's mother looked through the window; she [peered] through the lattice, crying out: "Why is his chariot so long in coming? Why don't I hear the hoofbeats of his horses?"
07Jdg 5:29 Her wisest princesses answer her; she even answers herself:
07Jdg 5:30 "Are they not finding and dividing the spoil-- a girl or two for each warrior, the spoil of colored garments for Sisera, the spoil of an embroidered garment or two for my neck?"
07Jdg 5:31 LORD, may all your enemies perish as Sisera did. But may those who love Him be like the rising of the sun in its strength. And the land was peaceful 40 years.
07Jdg 6:1 The Israelites did what was evil in the sight of the LORD. So the LORD handed them over to Midian seven years,
07Jdg 6:2 and they oppressed Israel. Because of Midian, the Israelites made hiding places for themselves in the mountains, caves, and strongholds.
07Jdg 6:3 Whenever the Israelites planted crops, the Midianites, Amalekites, and the eastern peoples came and attacked them.
07Jdg 6:4 They encamped against them and destroyed the produce of the land, even as far as Gaza. They left nothing for Israel to eat, as well as no sheep, ox or donkey.
07Jdg 6:5 For the Midianites came with their cattle and their tents like a great swarm of locusts. They and their camels were without number, and they entered the land to waste it.
07Jdg 6:6 So Israel became poverty stricken because of Midian, and the Israelites cried out to the LORD.
07Jdg 6:7 When the Israelites cried out to Him because of Midian,
07Jdg 6:8 the LORD sent a prophet to them. He said to them, "This is what the LORD God of Israel says: 'I brought you out of Egypt and out of the place of slavery.
07Jdg 6:9 I delivered you from the power of Egypt and the power of all who oppressed you. I drove them out before you and gave you their land.
07Jdg 6:10 I said to you: I am the LORD your God. Do not fear the gods of the Amorites whose land you live in. But you did not obey Me.'"
07Jdg 6:11 The Angel of the LORD came, and He sat under the oak that was in Ophrah, which belonged to Joash, the Abiezrite. His son Gideon was threshing wheat in the wine vat in order to hide it from the Midianites.
07Jdg 6:12 Then the Angel of the LORD appeared to him and said: "The LORD is with you, mighty warrior."
07Jdg 6:13 Gideon said to Him, "Please Sir, if the LORD is with us, why has all this happened? And where are all His wonders that our fathers told us about? They said, 'Hasn't the LORD brought us out of Egypt?' But now the LORD has abandoned us and handed us over to Midian."
07Jdg 6:14 The LORD turned to him and said, "Go in the strength you have and deliver Israel from the power of Midian. Am I not sending you?"
07Jdg 6:15 He said to Him, "Please, Lord, how can I deliver Israel? Look, my family is the weakest in Manasseh, and I am the youngest in my father's house."
07Jdg 6:16 "But I will be with you," the LORD said to him. "You will strike Midian down [as if it were] one man."
07Jdg 6:17 Then he said to Him, "If I have found favor in Your sight, give me a sign that You are speaking with me.
07Jdg 6:18 Please do not leave this place until I return to You. Let me bring my gift and set it before You." And He said, "I will stay until you return."
07Jdg 6:19 So Gideon went and prepared a young goat and unleavened bread from a half bushel of flour. He placed the meat in a basket and the broth in a pot. He brought them out and offered them to Him under the oak.
07Jdg 6:20 The Angel of God said to him, "Take the meat with the unleavened bread, put it on this stone, and pour the broth [on it]." And he did so.
07Jdg 6:21 The Angel of the LORD extended the tip of the staff that was in His hand and touched the meat and the unleavened bread. Fire came up from the rock and consumed the meat and the unleavened bread. Then the Angel of the LORD vanished from his sight.
07Jdg 6:22 When Gideon realized that He was the Angel of the LORD, he said, "Oh no, Lord God! I have seen the Angel of the LORD face to face!"
07Jdg 6:23 But the LORD said to him, "Peace to you. Don't be afraid, for you will not die."
07Jdg 6:24 So Gideon built an altar to the LORD there and called it Yahweh Shalom. It is in Ophrah of the Abiezrites until today.
07Jdg 6:25 On that very night the LORD said to him, "Take your father's young bull and a second bull seven years old. Then tear down the altar of Baal that belongs to your father and cut down the Asherah pole beside it.
07Jdg 6:26 Build a well-constructed altar to the LORD your God on the top of this rock. Take the second bull and offer it as a burnt offering with the wood of the Asherah pole you cut down."
07Jdg 6:27 So Gideon took 10 of his male servants and did as the LORD had told him. But because he was too afraid of his father's household and the men of the city to do it in the daytime, he did it at night.
07Jdg 6:28 When the men of the city got up in the morning, they found Baal's altar torn down, the Asherah pole beside it cut down, and the second bull offered up on the altar that had been built.
07Jdg 6:29 They said to each other, "Who did this?" After they made a thorough investigation, they said, "Gideon son of Joash did it."
07Jdg 6:30 Then the men of the city said to Joash, "Bring out your son. He must die, because he tore down Baal's altar and cut down the Asherah pole beside it."
07Jdg 6:31 But Joash said to all who stood against him, "Would you plead Baal's case for him? Would you save him? Whoever pleads his case will be put to death by morning! If he is a god, let him plead his own case, because someone tore down his altar."
07Jdg 6:32 That day, Gideon's father called him Jerubbaal, saying, "Let Baal plead his case with him," because he tore down his altar.
07Jdg 6:33 All the Midianites, Amalekites, and Qedemites gathered together, crossed over [the Jordan], and camped in the Valley of Jezreel.
07Jdg 6:34 The Spirit of the LORD enveloped Gideon, and he blew the ram's horn and the Abiezrites rallied behind him.
07Jdg 6:35 He sent messengers throughout all of Manasseh, who rallied behind him. He also sent messengers throughout Asher, Zebulun, and Naphtali, who [also] came to meet him.
07Jdg 6:36 Then Gideon said to God, "If You will deliver Israel by my hand, as You said,
07Jdg 6:37 I will put a fleece of wool here on the threshing floor. If dew is only on the fleece, and all the ground is dry, I will know that You will deliver Israel by my strength, as You said."
07Jdg 6:38 And that is what happened. When he got up early in the morning, he squeezed the fleece and wrung dew out of it, filling a bowl with water.
07Jdg 6:39 Gideon then said to God, "Don't be angry with me; let me speak one more time. Please allow me to make one more test with the fleece. Let it remain dry, and the dew be all over the ground."
07Jdg 6:40 That night God did [as Gideon requested]: only the fleece was dry, and dew was all over the ground.
07Jdg 7:1 Jerubbaal (that is, Gideon) and everyone who was with him, got up early and camped beside the spring of Harod. The camp of Midian was north of them, below the hill of Moreh, in the valley.
07Jdg 7:2 The LORD said to Gideon, "You have too many people for Me to hand the Midianites over to you, or else Israel might brag: 'I did it myself.'
07Jdg 7:3 Now announce in the presence of the people: 'Whoever is fearful and trembling may turn back and leave Mount Gilead.' " So 22,000 of the people turned back, but 10,000 remained.
07Jdg 7:4 Then the LORD said to Gideon, "There are still too many people. Take them down to the water, and I will test them for you there. If I say to you, 'This one can go with you,' he can go. But if I say about anyone, 'This one cannot go with you,' he cannot go."
07Jdg 7:5 So he brought the people down to the water, and the LORD said to Gideon, "Separate everyone who laps water with his tongue like a dog. Do the same with everyone who kneels to drink."
07Jdg 7:6 The number of those who lapped with their hands to their mouths was 300 men, and all the rest of the people knelt to drink water.
07Jdg 7:7 The LORD said to Gideon, "I will deliver you with the 300 men who lapped and hand the Midianites over to you. But everyone else is to go home."
07Jdg 7:8 So Gideon sent all the Israelites to their tents, but kept the 300 who took the people's provisions and their trumpets. The camp of Midian was below him in the valley.
07Jdg 7:9 That night the LORD said to him, "Get up and go into the camp, for I have given it into your hand.
07Jdg 7:10 But if you are afraid to go to the camp, go with Purah your servant.
07Jdg 7:11 Listen to what they say, and then you will be strengthened to go to the camp." So he went with Purah his servant to the outpost of the troops who were in the camp.
07Jdg 7:12 Now the Midianites, Amalekites, and all the Qedemites had settled down in the valley like a swarm of locusts, and their camels were as innumerable as the sand on the seashore.
07Jdg 7:13 When Gideon arrived, there was a man telling his friend [about] a dream. He said, "Listen, I had a dream: a loaf of barley bread came tumbling into the Midianite camp, struck a tent, and it fell. The loaf turned the tent upside down so that it collapsed."
07Jdg 7:14 His friend answered: "This is nothing less than the sword of Gideon son of Joash, the Israelite. God has handed the entire Midianite camp over to him."
07Jdg 7:15 When Gideon heard the account of the dream and its interpretation, he bowed in worship. He returned to Israel's camp and said, "Get up, for the LORD has handed the Midianite camp over to you."
07Jdg 7:16 Then he divided the 300 men into three companies and gave each of the men a trumpet in one hand and an empty pitcher with a torch inside it [in the other].
07Jdg 7:17 "Watch me," he said, "and do the same. When I come to the outpost of the camp, do as I do.
07Jdg 7:18 When I and everyone with me blow our trumpets, you are also to blow your trumpets all around the camp. Then you will say, 'The sword of the LORD and of Gideon!'"
07Jdg 7:19 Gideon and the 100 men who were with him went to the outpost of the camp at the beginning of the middle watch after the sentries had been stationed. They blew their trumpets and broke the pitchers that were in their hands.
07Jdg 7:20 The three companies blew their trumpets and shattered their pitchers. They held their torches in their left hands, their trumpets in their right hands, and shouted, "The sword of the LORD and of Gideon!"
07Jdg 7:21 Each Israelite took his position around the camp, and the entire [Midianite] army fled, and cried out as they ran.
07Jdg 7:22 When Gideon's men blew their 300 trumpets, the LORD set the swords of each man in the army against each other. They fled to Beth-shittah in the direction of Zererah as far as the border of Abel-meholah near Tabbath.
07Jdg 7:23 Then the men of Israel were called from Naphtali, Asher, and Manasseh, and they pursued the Midianites.
07Jdg 7:24 Gideon sent messengers throughout the hill country of Ephraim with this message: "Come down to intercept the Midianites and take control of the watercourses ahead of them as far as Beth-barah and the Jordan." So all the men of Ephraim were called out, and they took control of the watercourses as far as Beth-barah and the Jordan.
07Jdg 7:25 They captured Oreb and Zeeb, the two princes of Midian; they killed Oreb at the rock of Oreb and Zeeb at the winepress of Zeeb, while they were pursuing the Midianites. They brought the heads of Oreb and Zeeb to Gideon across the Jordan.
07Jdg 8:1 The men of Ephraim said to him, "Why have you done this to us, not calling us when you went to fight against the Midianites?" And they argued with him violently.
07Jdg 8:2 So he said to them, "What have I done now compared to you? Is not the gleaning of Ephraim better than the vintage of Abiezer?
07Jdg 8:3 God handed over to you Oreb and Zeeb, the two princes of Midian. What was I able to do compared to you?" When he said this, their anger against him subsided.
07Jdg 8:4 Gideon and the 300 men came to the Jordan and crossed it. They were exhausted, but still in pursuit.
07Jdg 8:5 He said to the men of Succoth, "Please give some loaves of bread to the people who are following me, because they are exhausted, for I am pursuing Zebah and Zalmunna, the kings of Midian."
07Jdg 8:6 But the princes of Succoth asked, "Are Zebah and Zalmunna now in your hands that we should give bread to your army?"
07Jdg 8:7 Gideon replied, "Very well, when the LORD has handed Zebah and Zalmunna over to me, I will trample your flesh on thorns and briers from the wilderness!"
07Jdg 8:8 He went from there to Penuel and asked the same thing from them. The men of Penuel answered just as the men of Succoth had answered.
07Jdg 8:9 He also told the men of Penuel, "When I return in peace, I will tear down this tower!"
07Jdg 8:10 Now Zebah and Zalmunna were in Karkor, and with them was their army of about 15,000 men, who were all those left of the entire army of the Qedemites. Those who had been killed were 120,000 warriors.
07Jdg 8:11 Gideon traveled on the caravan route, east of Nobah and Jogbehah, and attacked their army while the army was unsuspecting.
07Jdg 8:12 Zebah and Zalmunna fled, and he pursued them. He captured these two kings of Midian and routed the entire army.
07Jdg 8:13 Gideon son of Joash returned from the battle by the ascent of Heres.
07Jdg 8:14 He captured a youth from the men of Succoth and interrogated him. The youth wrote down for him the [names of the] 77 princes and elders of Succoth.
07Jdg 8:15 Then he went to the men of Succoth and said, "Here are Zebah and Zalmunna. You taunted me about them, saying, 'Are Zebah and Zalmunna now in your power that we should give bread to your exhausted men?'"
07Jdg 8:16 So he took the elders of the city, as well as some thorns and briers from the wilderness, and he disciplined the men of Succoth with them.
07Jdg 8:17 He also tore down the tower of Penuel and killed the men of the city.
07Jdg 8:18 He asked Zebah and Zalmunna, "What kind of men did you kill at Tabor?" "They were like you," they said. "Each resembled the son of a king."
07Jdg 8:19 So he said, "They were my brothers, the sons of my mother! As the LORD lives, if you had let them live, I would not kill you."
07Jdg 8:20 Then he said to Jether, his firstborn, "Get up and kill them." The youth did not draw his sword, because he was afraid, for he was still a youth.
07Jdg 8:21 Zebah and Zalmunna said, "Get up and kill us yourself, for a man is judged by his strength." So Gideon got up, killed Zebah and Zalmunna, and took the crescent ornaments that were on the necks of their camels.
07Jdg 8:22 Then the Israelites said to Gideon, "Rule over us, you as well as your sons and your grandsons, for you delivered us from the power of Midian."
07Jdg 8:23 But Gideon said to them, "I will not rule over you, and my son will not rule over you; the LORD will rule over you."
07Jdg 8:24 Then he said to them, "Let me make a request of you: Everyone give me an earring from his plunder." Now the enemy had gold earrings because they were Ishmaelites.
07Jdg 8:25 They said, "We agree to give them." So they spread out a mantle, and everyone threw an earring from his plunder on it.
07Jdg 8:26 The weight of the gold earrings he requested was about 43 pounds of gold, in addition to the crescent ornaments and ear pendants, the purple garments on the kings of Midian, and the chains on the necks of their camels.
07Jdg 8:27 Gideon made an ephod from all this and put it in Ophrah, his hometown. Then all Israel prostituted themselves with it there, and it became a snare to Gideon and his household.
07Jdg 8:28 So Midian was subdued before the Israelites, and they were no longer a threat. The land was peaceful 40 years during the days of Gideon.
07Jdg 8:29 Jerubbaal [(that is, Gideon)] son of Joash went back to live at his house.
07Jdg 8:30 Gideon had 70 sons, his own offspring, since he had many wives.
07Jdg 8:31 His concubine who was in Shechem also bore him a son, and he named him Abimelech.
07Jdg 8:32 Then Gideon son of Joash died at a ripe old age and was buried in the tomb of his father Joash in Ophrah of the Abiezrites.
07Jdg 8:33 When Gideon died, the Israelites turned and prostituted themselves with the Baals and made Baal-berith their god.
07Jdg 8:34 The Israelites did not remember the LORD their God who had delivered them from the power of the enemies around them.
07Jdg 8:35 They did not show kindness to the house of Jerubbaal ([that is,] Gideon) for all the good he had done for Israel.
07Jdg 9:1 Abimelech son of Jerubbaal went to his mother's brothers at Shechem and spoke to them and to all his maternal grandfather's clan, saying,
07Jdg 9:2 "Please speak in the presence of all the lords of Shechem, 'Is it better for you that 70 men, all the sons of Jerubbaal, rule over you or that one man rule over you?' Remember that I am your own flesh and blood."
07Jdg 9:3 His mother's relatives spoke all these words about him in the presence of all the lords of Shechem, and they were favorable to Abimelech, for they said, "He is our brother."
07Jdg 9:4 So they gave him 70 pieces of silver from the temple of Baal-berith. Abimelech hired worthless and reckless men with this money, and they followed him.
07Jdg 9:5 He went to his father's house in Ophrah and killed his 70 brothers, the sons of Jerubbaal, on top of a large stone. But Jotham, the youngest son of Jerubbaal, survived, because he hid himself.
07Jdg 9:6 Then all the lords of Shechem and of Beth-millo gathered together and proceeded to make Abimelech king at the oak of the pillar in Shechem.
07Jdg 9:7 When they told Jotham, he climbed to the top of Mount Gerizim, raised his voice, and called to them: Listen to me, lords of Shechem, and may God listen to you:
07Jdg 9:8 The trees set out to anoint a king over themselves. They said to the olive tree, "Reign over us."
07Jdg 9:9 But the olive tree said to them, "Should I stop giving my oil that honors both God and man, and rule over the trees?"
07Jdg 9:10 Then the trees said to the fig tree, "Come and reign over us."
07Jdg 9:11 But the fig tree said to them, "Should I stop giving my sweetness and my good fruit, and rule over trees?"
07Jdg 9:12 Later, the trees said to the grapevine, "Come and reign over us."
07Jdg 9:13 But the grapevine said to them, "Should I stop giving my wine that cheers both God and man, and rule over trees?"
07Jdg 9:14 Finally, all the trees said to the bramble, "Come and reign over us."
07Jdg 9:15 The bramble said to the trees, "If you really are anointing me as king over you, come and find refuge in my shade. But if not, may fire come out from the bramble and consume the cedars of Lebanon."
07Jdg 9:16 "Now if you have acted faithfully and honestly in making Abimelech king, if you have done well by Jerubbaal and his family, and if you have rewarded him appropriately for what he did--
07Jdg 9:17 for my father fought for you, risked his life, and delivered you from the hand of Midian,
07Jdg 9:18 and now you have attacked my father's house today, killed his 70 sons on top of a large stone, and made Abimelech, the son of his slave, king over the lords of Shechem 'because he is your brother'--
07Jdg 9:19 if then, you have acted faithfully and honestly with Jerubbaal and his house this day, rejoice in Abimelech and may he also rejoice in you.
07Jdg 9:20 But if not, may fire come from Abimelech and consume the lords of Shechem and Beth-millo, and may fire come from the lords of Shechem and Beth-millo and consume Abimelech."
07Jdg 9:21 Then Jotham fled, escaping to Beer, and lived there because of his brother Abimelech.
07Jdg 9:22 When Abimelech had ruled over Israel three years,
07Jdg 9:23 God sent an evil spirit between Abimelech and the lords of Shechem. They treated Abimelech deceitfully,
07Jdg 9:24 so that the crime against the 70 sons of Jerubbaal might come to justice and their blood would be avenged on their brother Abimelech, who killed them, and on the lords of Shechem, who had helped him kill his brothers.
07Jdg 9:25 The lords of Shechem rebelled against him by putting people on the tops of the mountains to ambush and rob everyone who passed by them on the road. So this was reported to Abimelech.
07Jdg 9:26 Gaal son of Ebed came with his brothers and crossed into Shechem, and the lords of Shechem trusted him.
07Jdg 9:27 So they went out to the countryside and harvested grapes from their vineyards. They trod the grapes and held a celebration. Then they went to the house of their god, and as they ate and drank, they cursed Abimelech.
07Jdg 9:28 Gaal son of Ebed said, "Who is Abimelech and who is Shechem that we should serve him? Isn't he the son of Jerubbaal, and isn't Zebul his officer? You are to serve the men of Hamor, the father of Shechem. Why should we serve Abimelech?
07Jdg 9:29 If only these people were in my power, I would remove Abimelech." So he said to Abimelech, "Gather your army and come out."
07Jdg 9:30 When Zebul, the ruler of the city, heard the words of Gaal son of Ebed, he was angry.
07Jdg 9:31 So he sent messengers secretly to Abimelech, saying, "Look, Gaal son of Ebed, with his brothers, have come to Shechem and are turning the city against you.
07Jdg 9:32 Now tonight, you and the people with you are to come wait in ambush in the countryside.
07Jdg 9:33 Then get up early and at sunrise, charge the city. When he and the people who are with him come out against you, do to him whatever you can."
07Jdg 9:34 So Abimelech and all the people with him got up at night and waited in ambush for Shechem in four units.
07Jdg 9:35 Gaal son of Ebed went out and stood at the entrance of the city gate. Then Abimelech and the people who were with him got up from their ambush.
07Jdg 9:36 When Gaal saw the people, he said to Zebul, "Look, people are coming down from the mountaintops!" But Zebul said to him, "The shadows of the mountains look like men to you."
07Jdg 9:37 Then Gaal spoke again: "Look, people are coming down from the central part of the land, and one unit is coming from the direction of the Diviners' Oak."
07Jdg 9:38 Zebul replied, "Where is your mouthing off now? You said, 'Who is Abimelech that we should serve him?' Aren't these the people you despised? Now go and fight them!"
07Jdg 9:39 So Gaal went out leading the lords of Shechem and fought against Abimelech,
07Jdg 9:40 but Abimelech pursued him, and Gaal fled before him. Many wounded died as far as the entrance of the gate.
07Jdg 9:41 Abimelech stayed in Arumah, and Zebul drove Gaal and his brothers from Shechem.
07Jdg 9:42 The next day when the people went into the countryside, this was reported to Abimelech.
07Jdg 9:43 He took the people, divided them into three companies, and waited in ambush in the countryside. He looked, and the people were coming out of the city, so he arose against them and struck them down.
07Jdg 9:44 Then Abimelech and the units that were with him rushed forward and took their stand at the entrance of the city gate. The other two units rushed against all who were in the countryside and struck them down.
07Jdg 9:45 So Abimelech fought against the city that entire day, captured it, and killed the people who were in it. Then he tore down the city and sowed it with salt.
07Jdg 9:46 When all the lords of the Tower of Shechem heard, they entered the inner chamber of the temple of El-berith.
07Jdg 9:47 Then it was reported to Abimelech that all the lords of the Tower of Shechem had gathered together.
07Jdg 9:48 So Abimelech and all the people who were with him went up to Mount Zalmon. Abimelech took his ax in his hand and cut a branch from the trees. He picked up the branch, put it on his shoulder, and said to the people who were with him, "Hurry and do what you have seen me do."
07Jdg 9:49 Each person also cut his own branch and followed Abimelech. They put the branches against the inner chamber and set it on fire around the people, and all the people in the Tower of Shechem died-- about 1,000 men and women.
07Jdg 9:50 Abimelech went to Thebez, camped against it, and captured it.
07Jdg 9:51 There was a strong tower inside the city, and all the men, women, and lords of the city fled there. They locked themselves in and went up to the roof of the tower.
07Jdg 9:52 When Abimelech came to attack the tower, he approached its entrance to set it on fire.
07Jdg 9:53 But a woman threw the upper portion of a millstone on Abimelech's head and fractured his skull.
07Jdg 9:54 He quickly called his armor-bearer and said to him, "Draw your sword and kill me, or they'll say about me, 'A woman killed him.' " So his armor-bearer thrust him through, and he died.
07Jdg 9:55 When the Israelites saw that Abimelech was dead, they all went home.
07Jdg 9:56 In this way, the evil that Abimelech had done against his father, by killing his 70 brothers, God turned back on him.
07Jdg 9:57 And God also returned all the evil of the men of Shechem on their heads. So the curse of Jotham son of Jerubbaal came on them.
07Jdg 10:1 After Abimelech, Tola son of Puah, son of Dodo [became judge] and began to deliver Israel. He was from Issachar and lived in Shamir in the hill country of Ephraim.
07Jdg 10:2 Tola judged Israel 23 years, and when he died, was buried in Shamir.
07Jdg 10:3 After him came Jair the Gileadite, who judged Israel 22 years.
07Jdg 10:4 He had 30 sons who rode on 30 young donkeys. They had 30 towns in Gilead, which are called Jair's Villages to this day.
07Jdg 10:5 When Jair died, he was buried in Kamon.
07Jdg 10:6 Then the Israelites again did what was evil in the sight of the LORD. They worshiped the Baals and the Ashtoreths, the gods of Aram, Sidon, and Moab, and the gods of the Ammonites and the Philistines. They abandoned the LORD and did not worship Him.
07Jdg 10:7 So the LORD's anger burned against Israel, and He sold them to the Philistines and the Ammonites.
07Jdg 10:8 They shattered and crushed the Israelites that year, and for 18 years [they did the same to] all the Israelites who were on the other side of the Jordan in the land of the Amorites in Gilead.
07Jdg 10:9 The Ammonites also crossed the Jordan to fight against Judah, Benjamin, and the house of Ephraim. Israel was greatly oppressed,
07Jdg 10:10 so they cried out to the LORD, saying, "We have sinned against You. We have abandoned our God and worshiped the Baals."
07Jdg 10:11 The LORD said to the Israelites, "When the Egyptians, Amorites, Ammonites, Philistines,
07Jdg 10:12 Sidonians, Amalekites, and Maonites oppressed you, and you cried out to Me, did I not deliver you from their power?
07Jdg 10:13 But you have abandoned Me and worshiped other gods. Therefore, I will not deliver you again.
07Jdg 10:14 Go and cry out to the gods you have chosen. Let them deliver you in the time of your oppression."
07Jdg 10:15 But the Israelites said, "We have sinned. Deal with us as You see fit; only deliver us today!"
07Jdg 10:16 So they got rid of the foreign gods among them and worshiped the LORD, but He became weary of Israel's misery.
07Jdg 10:17 The Ammonites were called together, and they camped in Gilead. So the Israelites assembled and camped at Mizpah.
07Jdg 10:18 The rulers of Gilead said to one another, "Which man will lead the fight against the Ammonites? He will be the leader of all the inhabitants of Gilead."
07Jdg 11:1 Jephthah the Gileadite was a great warrior, but he was the son of a prostitute, and Gilead was his father.
07Jdg 11:2 Gilead's wife bore him sons, and when they grew up, they drove Jephthah out and said to him, "You will have no inheritance in our father's house, because you are the son of another woman."
07Jdg 11:3 So Jephthah fled from his brothers and lived in the land of Tob. Then some lawless men joined Jephthah and traveled with him.
07Jdg 11:4 Some time later, the Ammonites fought against Israel.
07Jdg 11:5 When the Ammonites made war with Israel, the elders of Gilead went to get Jephthah from the land of Tob.
07Jdg 11:6 They said to him, "Come, be our commander, and let's fight against the Ammonites."
07Jdg 11:7 Jephthah replied to the elders of Gilead, "Didn't you hate me and drive me from my father's house? Why then have you come to me now when you're in trouble?"
07Jdg 11:8 They answered Jephthah, "Since that's true, we now turn to you. Come with us, fight the Ammonites, and you will become leader of all the inhabitants of Gilead."
07Jdg 11:9 So Jephthah said to them, "If you are bringing me back to fight the Ammonites and the LORD gives them to me, I will be your leader."
07Jdg 11:10 The elders of Gilead said to Jephthah, "The LORD is our witness if we don't do as you say."
07Jdg 11:11 So Jephthah went with the elders of Gilead. The people put him over themselves as leader and commander, and Jephthah repeated all his terms in the presence of the LORD at Mizpah.
07Jdg 11:12 Jephthah sent messengers to the king of the Ammonites, saying, "What do you have against me that you have come to fight against me in my land?"
07Jdg 11:13 The king of the Ammonites said to Jephthah's messengers, "When Israel came from Egypt, they seized my land from the Arnon to the Jabbok and the Jordan. Now restore it peaceably."
07Jdg 11:14 Jephthah again sent messengers to the king of the Ammonites
07Jdg 11:15 to tell him, "This is what Jephthah says: Israel did not take away the land of Moab or the land of the Ammonites.
07Jdg 11:16 But when they came from Egypt, Israel traveled through the wilderness to the Red Sea and came to Kadesh.
07Jdg 11:17 Israel sent messengers to the king of Edom, saying, 'Please let us travel through your land,' but the king of Edom would not listen. They also sent [messengers] to the king of Moab, but he refused. So Israel stayed in Kadesh.
07Jdg 11:18 "Then they traveled through the wilderness and around the lands of Edom and Moab. They came to the east side of the land of Moab and camped on the other side of the Arnon but did not enter into the territory of Moab, for the Arnon was the boundary of Moab.
07Jdg 11:19 "Then Israel sent messengers to Sihon king of the Amorites, king of Heshbon. Israel said to him, 'Please let us travel through your land to our country,'
07Jdg 11:20 but Sihon did not trust Israel. Instead, Sihon gathered all his people, camped at Jahaz, and fought with Israel.
07Jdg 11:21 Then the LORD God of Israel handed over Sihon and all his people to Israel, and they defeated them. So Israel took possession of the entire land of the Amorites who lived in that country.
07Jdg 11:22 They took possession of all the territory of the Amorites from the Arnon to the Jabbok and from the wilderness to the Jordan.
07Jdg 11:23 "The LORD God of Israel has now driven out the Amorites before His people Israel, but will you drive us out?
07Jdg 11:24 Isn't it true that you may possess whatever your god Chemosh drives out for you, and we may possess everything the LORD our God drives out before us?
07Jdg 11:25 Now are you any better than Balak son of Zippor, king of Moab? Did he ever contend with Israel or fight against them?
07Jdg 11:26 While Israel lived 300 years in Heshbon and its villages, in Aroer and its villages, and in all the cities that are on the banks of the Arnon, why didn't you take them back at that time?
07Jdg 11:27 I have not sinned against you, but you have wronged me by fighting against me. Let the LORD [who is] the Judge decide today between the Israelites and the Ammonites."
07Jdg 11:28 But the king of the Ammonites would not listen to Jephthah's message that he sent him.
07Jdg 11:29 The Spirit of the LORD came on Jephthah, who traveled through Gilead and Manasseh, and then through Mizpah of Gilead. He crossed over to the Ammonites from Mizpah of Gilead.
07Jdg 11:30 Jephthah made this vow to the LORD: "If You will hand over the Ammonites to me,
07Jdg 11:31 whatever comes out of the doors of my house to greet me when I return in peace from the Ammonites will belong to the LORD, and I will offer it as a burnt offering."
07Jdg 11:32 Jephthah crossed over to the Ammonites to fight against them, and the LORD handed them over to him.
07Jdg 11:33 He defeated 20 of their cities with a great slaughter from Aroer all the way to the entrance of Minnith and to Abel-keramim. So the Ammonites were subdued before the Israelites.
07Jdg 11:34 When Jephthah went to his home in Mizpah, there was his daughter, coming out to meet him with tambourines and dancing! She was his only child; he had no other son or daughter besides her.
07Jdg 11:35 When he saw her, he tore his clothes and said, "No! [Not] my daughter! You have devastated me! You have brought great misery on me. I have given my word to the LORD and cannot take [it] back.
07Jdg 11:36 Then she said to him, "My father, you have given your word to the LORD. Do to me as you have said, for the LORD brought vengeance on your enemies, the Ammonites."
07Jdg 11:37 She also said to her father, "Let me do this one thing: Let me wander two months through the mountains with my friends and mourn my virginity."
07Jdg 11:38 "Go," he said. And he sent her away two months. So she left with her friends and mourned her virginity as she wandered through the mountains.
07Jdg 11:39 At the end of two months, she returned to her father, and he kept the vow he had made about her. And she had never been intimate with a man. Now it became a custom in Israel
07Jdg 11:40 [that] four days each year the young women of Israel would commemorate the daughter of Jephthah the Gileadite.
07Jdg 12:1 The men of Ephraim were called together and crossed [the Jordan] to Zaphon. They said to Jephthah, "Why have you crossed over to fight against the Ammonites but didn't call us to go with you? We will burn your house down with you [in it]!"
07Jdg 12:2 Then Jephthah said to them, "My people and I had a serious conflict with the Ammonites. So I called for you, but you didn't deliver me from their power.
07Jdg 12:3 When I saw that you weren't going to deliver me, I took my life in my own hands and crossed over to the Ammonites, and the LORD handed them over to me. Why then have you come today to fight against me?"
07Jdg 12:4 Then Jephthah gathered all of the men of Gilead. They fought and defeated Ephraim, because Ephraim had said, "You Gileadites are Ephraimite fugitives in [the territories of] Ephraim and Manasseh."
07Jdg 12:5 The Gileadites captured the fords of the Jordan leading to Ephraim. Whenever a fugitive from Ephraim said, "Let me cross over," the Gileadites asked him, "Are you an Ephraimite?" If he answered, "No,"
07Jdg 12:6 they told him, "Please say Shibboleth." If he said, "Sibboleth," because he could not pronounce it correctly, they seized him and killed him at the fords of the Jordan. At that time, 42,000 from Ephraim died.
07Jdg 12:7 Jephthah judged Israel six years, and when he died, he was buried in one of the cities of Gilead.
07Jdg 12:8 Ibzan, who was from Bethlehem, judged Israel after Jephthah
07Jdg 12:9 and had 30 sons. He gave his 30 daughters in marriage [to men] outside the tribe and brought back 30 wives for his sons from outside [the tribe]. Ibzan judged Israel seven years,
07Jdg 12:10 and when he died, he was buried in Bethlehem.
07Jdg 12:11 Elon, who was from Zebulun, judged Israel after Ibzan. He judged Israel 10 years,
07Jdg 12:12 and when he died, he was buried in Aijalon in the land of Zebulun.
07Jdg 12:13 After Elon, Abdon son of Hillel, who was from Pirathon, judged Israel.
07Jdg 12:14 He had 40 sons and 30 grandsons, who rode on 70 donkeys. Abdon judged Israel eight years,
07Jdg 12:15 and when he died, he was buried in Pirathon in the land of Ephraim, in the hill country of the Amalekites.
07Jdg 13:1 The Israelites again did what was evil in the LORD's sight, so the LORD handed them over to the Philistines 40 years.
07Jdg 13:2 There was a certain man from Zorah, from the family of Dan, whose name was Manoah; his wife was barren and had no children.
07Jdg 13:3 The Angel of the LORD appeared to the woman and said to her, "It is true that you are barren and have no children, but you will conceive and give birth to a son.
07Jdg 13:4 Now please be careful not to drink wine or other alcoholic beverages, or to eat anything unclean;
07Jdg 13:5 for indeed, you will conceive and give birth to a son. You must never cut his hair, because the boy will be a Nazirite to God from birth, and he will begin to save Israel from the power of the Philistines."
07Jdg 13:6 Then the woman went and told her husband, "A man of God came to me. He looked like the awe-inspiring Angel of God. I didn't ask Him where He came from, and He didn't tell me His name.
07Jdg 13:7 He said to me, 'You will conceive and give a birth to a son. Therefore, do not drink wine or other alcoholic beverages, and do not eat anything unclean, because the boy will be a Nazirite to God from birth until the day of his death.'"
07Jdg 13:8 Manoah prayed to the LORD and said, "Please Lord, let the man of God you sent come again to us and teach us what we should do for the boy who will be born."
07Jdg 13:9 God listened to Manoah, and the Angel of God came again to the woman. She was sitting in the field, and her husband Manoah was not with her.
07Jdg 13:10 The woman ran quickly to her husband and told him, "The man who came to me today has just come back!"
07Jdg 13:11 So Manoah got up and followed his wife. When he came to the man, he asked, "Are You the man who spoke to my wife?" "I am," He said.
07Jdg 13:12 Then Manoah asked, "When Your words come true, what will the boy's responsibilities and mission be?"
07Jdg 13:13 The Angel of the LORD answered Manoah, "Your wife needs to do everything I told her.
07Jdg 13:14 She must not eat anything that comes from the grapevine or drink wine or other alcoholic beverages. And she must not eat anything unclean. Your wife must do everything I have commanded her."
07Jdg 13:15 "Please stay here," Manoah told Him, "and we will prepare a young goat for You."
07Jdg 13:16 The Angel of the LORD said to him, "If I stay, I won't eat your food. But if you want to prepare a burnt offering, offer it to the LORD." For Manoah did not know He was the Angel of the LORD.
07Jdg 13:17 Then Manoah said to Him, "What is Your name, so that we may honor You when Your words come true?"
07Jdg 13:18 "Why do you ask My name," the Angel of the LORD asked him, "since it is wonderful."
07Jdg 13:19 Manoah took a young goat and a grain offering and offered them on a rock to the LORD, and He did a wonderful thing while Manoah and his wife were watching.
07Jdg 13:20 When the flame went up from the altar to the sky, the Angel of the LORD went up in its flame. When Manoah and his wife saw [this], they fell facedown on the ground.
07Jdg 13:21 The Angel of the LORD did not appear again to Manoah and his wife. Then Manoah realized that it was the Angel of the LORD.
07Jdg 13:22 "We're going to die," he said to his wife, "because we have seen God!"
07Jdg 13:23 But his wife said to him, "If the LORD had intended to kill us, He wouldn't have accepted the burnt offering and the grain offering from us, and He would not have shown us all these things or spoken to us now like this."
07Jdg 13:24 So the woman gave birth to a son and named him Samson. The boy grew, and the LORD blessed him.
07Jdg 13:25 Then the Spirit of the LORD began to direct him in the Camp of Dan, between Zorah and Eshtaol.
07Jdg 14:1 Samson went down to Timnah and saw a young Philistine woman there.
07Jdg 14:2 He went back and told his father and his mother: "I have seen a young Philistine woman in Timnah. Now get her for me as a wife."
07Jdg 14:3 But his father and mother said to him, "Can't you find a young woman among your relatives or among any of our people? Must you go to the uncircumcised Philistines for a wife?" But Samson told his father, "Get her for me, because I want her."
07Jdg 14:4 Now his father and mother did not know this was from the LORD, who was seeking an occasion against the Philistines. At that time, the Philistines were ruling over Israel.
07Jdg 14:5 Samson went down to Timnah with his father and mother and came to the vineyards of Timnah. Suddenly a young lion came roaring at him,
07Jdg 14:6 the Spirit of the LORD took control of him, and he tore the lion apart with his bare hands as he might have torn a young goat. But he did not tell his father or mother what he had done.
07Jdg 14:7 Then he went and spoke to the woman, because Samson wanted her.
07Jdg 14:8 After some time, when he returned to get her, he left [the road] to see the lion's carcass, and there was a swarm of bees with honey in the carcass.
07Jdg 14:9 He scooped [some honey] into his hands and ate [it] as he went along. When he returned to his father and mother, he gave [some] to them and they ate [it]. But he did not tell them that he had scooped the honey from the lion's carcass.
07Jdg 14:10 His father went [to visit] the woman, and Samson prepared a feast there, as young men were accustomed to do.
07Jdg 14:11 When the Philistines saw him, they brought 30 men to accompany him.
07Jdg 14:12 "Let me tell you a riddle," Samson said to them. "If you can explain it to me during the seven days of the feast and figure it out, I will give you 30 linen garments and 30 changes of clothes.
07Jdg 14:13 But if you can't explain it to me, you must give me 30 linen garments and 30 changes of clothes." "Tell us your riddle," they replied. "Let's hear it."
07Jdg 14:14 So he said to them: Out of the eater came something to eat, and out of the strong came something sweet. After three days, they were unable to explain the riddle.
07Jdg 14:15 On the fourth day they said to Samson's wife, "Persuade your husband to explain the riddle to us, or we will burn you and your father's household to death. Did you invite us here to rob us?"
07Jdg 14:16 So Samson's wife came to him, weeping, and said, "You hate me and don't love me! You told my people the riddle, but haven't explained it to me." "Look," he said, "I haven't even explained it to my father or mother, so [why] should I explain it to you?"
07Jdg 14:17 She wept the whole seven days of the feast, and at last, on the seventh day, he explained it to her, because she had nagged him so much. Then she explained it to her people.
07Jdg 14:18 On the seventh day before sunset, the men of the city said to him: What is sweeter than honey? What is stronger than a lion? So he said to them: If you hadn't plowed with my young cow, you wouldn't know my riddle now!
07Jdg 14:19 The Spirit of the LORD took control of him, and he went down to Ashkelon and killed 30 of their men. He stripped them and gave their clothes to those who had explained the riddle. In a rage, Samson returned to his father's house,
07Jdg 14:20 and his wife was given to one of the men who had accompanied him.
07Jdg 15:1 Later on, during the wheat harvest, Samson [took] a young goat [as a gift] and visited his wife. "I want to go to my wife in her room," he said. But her father would not let him enter.
07Jdg 15:2 "I was sure you hated her," her father said, "so I gave her to one of the men who accompanied you. Isn't her younger sister more beautiful than she is? Why not take her instead?"
07Jdg 15:3 Samson said to them, "This time I won't be responsible when I harm the Philistines."
07Jdg 15:4 So he went out and caught 300 foxes. He took torches, turned the foxes tail-to-tail, and put a torch between each pair of tails.
07Jdg 15:5 Then he ignited the torches and released the foxes into the standing grain of the Philistines. He burned up the piles of grain and the standing grain as well as the vineyards and olive groves.
07Jdg 15:6 Then the Philistines asked, "Who did this?" They were told, "[It was] Samson, the Timnite's son-in-law, because he has taken Samson's wife and given her to another man." So the Philistines went to her and her father and burned [them] to death.
07Jdg 15:7 Then Samson told them, "Because you did this, I swear that I won't rest until I have taken vengeance on you."
07Jdg 15:8 He tore them limb from limb with a great slaughter, and he went down and stayed in the cave at the rock of Etam.
07Jdg 15:9 The Philistines went up, camped in Judah, and raided Lehi.
07Jdg 15:10 So the men of Judah said, "Why have you attacked us?" They replied, "We have come to arrest Samson and pay him back for what he did to us."
07Jdg 15:11 Then 3,000 men of Judah went to the cave at the rock of Etam, and they asked Samson, "Don't you realize that the Philistines rule over us? What have you done to us?" "I have done to them what they did to me," he answered.
07Jdg 15:12 They said to him, "We've come to arrest you and hand you over to the Philistines." Then Samson told them, "Swear to me that you yourselves won't kill me."
07Jdg 15:13 "No," they said, "we won't kill you, but we will tie you up securely and hand you over to them." So they tied him up with two new ropes and led him away from the rock.
07Jdg 15:14 When he came to Lehi, the Philistines came to meet him shouting. The Spirit of the LORD took control of him, and the ropes that were on his arms became like burnt flax and his bonds fell off his wrists.
07Jdg 15:15 He found a fresh jawbone of a donkey, reached out his hand, took it, and killed 1,000 men with it.
07Jdg 15:16 Then Samson said: With the jawbone of a donkey I have piled them in a heap. With the jawbone of a donkey I have killed 1,000 men.
07Jdg 15:17 When he finished speaking, he threw away the jawbone and named that place Ramath-lehi.
07Jdg 15:18 He became very thirsty and called out to the LORD: "You have accomplished this great victory through Your servant. Must I now die of thirst and fall into the hands of the uncircumcised?"
07Jdg 15:19 So God split a hollow place [in the ground] at Lehi, and water came out of it. After Samson drank, his strength returned, and he revived. That is why he named it En-hakkore, which is in Lehi to this day.
07Jdg 15:20 And he judged Israel 20 years in the days of the Philistines.
07Jdg 16:1 Samson went to Gaza, where he saw a prostitute and went to bed with her.
07Jdg 16:2 When the Gazites [heard] that Samson was there, they surrounded the place and waited in ambush for him all that night at the city gate. While they were waiting quietly, they said, "Let us wait until dawn; then we will kill him."
07Jdg 16:3 But Samson stayed in bed until midnight when he got up, took hold of the doors of the city gate along with the two gateposts, and pulled them out, bar and all. He put them on his shoulders and took them to the top of the mountain overlooking Hebron.
07Jdg 16:4 Some time later, he fell in love with a woman named Delilah, who lived in the Sorek Valley.
07Jdg 16:5 The Philistine leaders went to her and said, "Persuade him to tell you where his great strength comes from, so we can overpower him, tie him up, and make him helpless. Each of us will then give you 1,100 pieces of silver."
07Jdg 16:6 So Delilah said to Samson, "Please tell me, where does your great strength [come from]? How could [someone] tie you up and make you helpless?"
07Jdg 16:7 Samson told her, "If they tie me up with seven fresh bowstrings that have not been dried, I will become weak and be like any other man."
07Jdg 16:8 The Philistine leaders brought her seven fresh bowstrings that had not been dried, and she tied him up with them.
07Jdg 16:9 While the men in ambush were waiting in her room, she called out to him, "Samson, the Philistines are here!" But he snapped the bowstrings as a strand of yarn snaps when it touches fire. [The secret of] his strength remained unknown.
07Jdg 16:10 Then Delilah said to Samson, "You have mocked me and told me lies! Won't you please tell me how you can be tied up?"
07Jdg 16:11 He told her, "If they tie me up with new ropes that have never been used, I will become weak and be like any other man."
07Jdg 16:12 Delilah took new ropes, tied him up with them, and shouted, "Samson, the Philistines are here!" But while the men in ambush were waiting in her room, he snapped the ropes off his arms like a thread.
07Jdg 16:13 Then Delilah said to Samson, "You have mocked me all along and told me lies! Tell me how you can be tied up." He told her, "If you weave the seven braids on my head with the web of a loom--"
07Jdg 16:14 She fastened the braids with a pin and called to him, "Samson, the Philistines are here!" He awoke from his sleep and pulled out the pin, with the loom and the web.
07Jdg 16:15 "How can you say, 'I love you,' " she told him, "when your heart is not with me? This is the third time you have mocked me and not told me what makes your strength so great!"
07Jdg 16:16 Because she nagged him day after day and pled with him until she wore him out,
07Jdg 16:17 he told her the whole truth and said to her, "My hair has never been cut, because I am a Nazirite to God from birth. If I am shaved, my strength will leave me, and I will become weak and be like any other man."
07Jdg 16:18 When Delilah realized that he had told her the whole truth, she sent this message to the Philistine leaders: "Come one more time, for he has told me the whole truth." The Philistine leaders came to her and brought the money with them.
07Jdg 16:19 Then she let him fall asleep on her lap and called a man to shave off the seven braids on his head. In this way, she rendered him helpless, and his strength left him.
07Jdg 16:20 Then she cried, "Samson, the Philistines are here!" When he awoke from his sleep, he said, "I will escape as I did before and shake myself free." But he did not know that the LORD had left him.
07Jdg 16:21 The Philistines seized him and gouged out his eyes. They brought him down to Gaza and bound him with bronze shackles, and he was forced to grind grain in the prison.
07Jdg 16:22 But his hair began to grow back after it had been shaved.
07Jdg 16:23 Now the Philistine leaders gathered together to offer a great sacrifice to their god Dagon. They rejoiced and said: Our god has handed over our enemy Samson to us.
07Jdg 16:24 When the people saw him, they praised their god and said: Our god has handed over to us our enemy who destroyed our land and who multiplied our dead.
07Jdg 16:25 When they were drunk, they said, "Bring Samson here to entertain us." So they brought Samson from prison, and he entertained them. They had him stand between the pillars.
07Jdg 16:26 Samson said to the young man who was leading him by the hand, "Lead me where I can feel the pillars supporting the temple, so I can lean against them."
07Jdg 16:27 The temple was full of men and women; all the leaders of the Philistines were there, and about 3,000 men and women were on the roof watching Samson entertain [them].
07Jdg 16:28 He called out to the LORD: "Lord God, please remember me. Strengthen me, God, just once more. With one act of vengeance, let me pay back the Philistines for my two eyes."
07Jdg 16:29 Samson took hold of the two middle pillars supporting the temple and leaned against them, one on his right hand and the other on his left.
07Jdg 16:30 Samson said, "Let me die with the Philistines." He pushed with all his might, and the temple fell on the leaders and all the people in it. And the dead he killed at his death were more than those he had killed in his life.
07Jdg 16:31 Then his brothers and his father's family came down, carried him back, and buried him between Zorah and Eshtaol in the tomb of his father Manoah. So he judged Israel 20 years.
07Jdg 17:1 There was a man from the hill country of Ephraim named Micah.
07Jdg 17:2 He said to his mother, "The 1,100 pieces of silver taken from you, and that I heard you utter a curse about-- here, I have the silver with me. I took it. So now I return it to you." Then his mother said, "My son, you are blessed by the LORD!"
07Jdg 17:3 He returned the 1,100 pieces of silver to his mother, and his mother said, "I personally consecrate the silver to the LORD for my son's benefit to make a carved image overlaid with silver."
07Jdg 17:4 So he returned the silver to his mother, and she took five pounds of silver and gave it to a silversmith. He made it into a carved image overlaid with silver, and it was in Micah's house.
07Jdg 17:5 This man Micah had a shrine, and he made an ephod and household idols, and installed one of his sons to be his priest.
07Jdg 17:6 In those days there was no king in Israel; everyone did whatever he wanted.
07Jdg 17:7 There was a young man, a Levite, from Bethlehem in Judah, who resided within the clan of Judah.
07Jdg 17:8 The man left the town of Bethlehem in Judah to settle wherever he could find a place. On his way he came to Micah's home in the hill country of Ephraim.
07Jdg 17:9 "Where do you come from?" Micah asked him. He answered him, "I am a Levite from Bethlehem in Judah, and I'm going to settle wherever I can find a place.
07Jdg 17:10 Micah replied, "Stay with me and be my father and priest, and I will give you four ounces of silver a year, along with your clothing and provisions." So the Levite went in
07Jdg 17:11 and agreed to stay with the man, and the young man became like one of his sons.
07Jdg 17:12 Micah consecrated the Levite, and the young man became his priest and lived in Micah's house.
07Jdg 17:13 Then Micah said, "Now I know that the LORD will be good to me, because a Levite has become my priest."
07Jdg 18:1 In those days, there was no king in Israel, and the Danite tribe was looking for territory to occupy. Up to that time no territory had been captured [by them] among the tribes of Israel.
07Jdg 18:2 So the Danites sent out five brave men from all their clans, from Zorah and Eshtaol, to spy out the land and explore it. They told them, "Go and explore the land." They came to the hill country of Ephraim as far as the home of Micah and spent the night there.
07Jdg 18:3 While they were near Micah's home, they recognized the speech of the young Levite. So they went over to him and asked, "Who brought you here? What are you doing in this place? What is keeping you here?"
07Jdg 18:4 He told them what Micah had for him and that he had hired him as his priest.
07Jdg 18:5 Then they said to him, "Please inquire of God so we will know if we will have a successful journey."
07Jdg 18:6 The priest told them, "Go in peace. The LORD is watching over the journey you are going on."
07Jdg 18:7 The five men left and came to Laish. They saw that the people who were there were living securely, in the same way as the Sidonians, quiet and unsuspecting. There was nothing lacking in the land and no oppressive ruler. They were far from the Sidonians, having no alliance with anyone.
07Jdg 18:8 When the men went back to their clans at Zorah and Eshtaol, their people asked them, "What did you find out?"
07Jdg 18:9 They answered, "Come on, let's go up against them, for we have seen the land, and it is very good. Why wait? Don't hesitate to go and invade and take possession of the land!
07Jdg 18:10 When you get there, you will come to an unsuspecting people and a wide-open land, for God has handed it over to you. It is a place where nothing on earth is lacking."
07Jdg 18:11 Six hundred Danites departed from Zorah and Eshtaol armed with weapons of war.
07Jdg 18:12 They went up and camped at Kiriath-jearim in Judah. This is why the place is called the Camp of Dan to this day; it is west of Kiriath-jearim.
07Jdg 18:13 From there they traveled to the hill country of Ephraim and arrived at Micah's house.
07Jdg 18:14 The five men who had gone to spy out the land of Laish told their brothers, "Did you know that there are an ephod, household gods, and a carved image overlaid with silver in these houses? Now think about what you should do."
07Jdg 18:15 So they detoured there and went to the house of the young Levite at the home of Micah and greeted him.
07Jdg 18:16 The 600 Danite men were standing by the entrance of the gate, armed with their weapons of war.
07Jdg 18:17 Then the five men who had gone to spy out the land went in and took the carved image overlaid with silver, the ephod, and the household idols, while the priest was standing by the entrance of the gate with the 600 men armed with weapons of war.
07Jdg 18:18 When they entered Micah's house and took the carved image overlaid with silver, the ephod, and the household idols, the priest said to them, "What are you doing?"
07Jdg 18:19 They told him, "Be quiet. Keep your mouth shut. Come with us and be a father and a priest to us. Is it better for you to be a priest for the house of one person or for you to be a priest for a tribe and family in Israel?"
07Jdg 18:20 So the priest was pleased and took his ephod, household idols, and carved image, and went with the people.
07Jdg 18:21 They prepared to leave, putting their small children, livestock, and possessions in front of them.
07Jdg 18:22 After they were some distance from Micah's house, the men who were in the houses near it mobilized and caught up with the Danites.
07Jdg 18:23 They called to the Danites, who turned to face them, and said to Micah, "What's the matter with you that you mobilized [the men]?"
07Jdg 18:24 He said, "You took the gods I had made and the priest, and went away. What do I have left? How can you say to me, 'What's the matter with you?'"
07Jdg 18:25 The Danites said to him, "Don't raise your voice against us, or angry men will attack you, and you and your family will lose your lives."
07Jdg 18:26 The Danites went on their way, and Micah turned to go back home, because he saw that they were stronger than he was.
07Jdg 18:27 After they had taken the gods Micah had made and the priest that belonged to him, they went to Laish, to a quiet and unsuspecting people. They killed them with their swords and burned down the city.
07Jdg 18:28 There was no one to save them, because it was far from Sidon and they had no alliance with anyone. It was in a valley that belonged to Beth-rehob. They rebuilt the city and lived in it.
07Jdg 18:29 They named the city Dan, after the name of their ancestor Dan, who was born to Israel. The city was formerly named Laish.
07Jdg 18:30 The Danites set up the carved image for themselves. Jonathan son of Gershom, son of Moses, and his sons were priests for the Danite tribe until the time of the exile from the land.
07Jdg 18:31 So they set up for themselves Micah's carved image that he had made, [and it was there] as long as the house of God was in Shiloh.
07Jdg 19:1 In those days, when there was no king in Israel, a Levite living in a remote part of the hill country of Ephraim acquired a woman from Bethlehem in Judah as his concubine.
07Jdg 19:2 But she was unfaithful to him and left him for her father's house in Bethlehem in Judah. She was there for a period of four months.
07Jdg 19:3 Then her husband got up and went after her to speak kindly to her and bring her back. His servant and a couple of donkeys were with him. So she brought him to her father's house, and when the girl's father saw him, he gladly welcomed him.
07Jdg 19:4 His father-in-law, the girl's father, detained him, and he stayed with him for three days. They ate, drank, and spent the nights there.
07Jdg 19:5 On the fourth day, they got up early in the morning and prepared to go, but the girl's father said to his son-in-law, "Have something to eat to keep up your strength and then you can go."
07Jdg 19:6 So they sat down and the two of them ate and drank together. Then the girl's father said to the man, "Please agree to stay overnight and enjoy yourself."
07Jdg 19:7 The man got up to go, but his father-in-law persuaded him, so he stayed and spent the night there again.
07Jdg 19:8 He got up early in the morning of the fifth day to leave, but the girl's father said to him, "Please keep up your strength." So they waited until late afternoon and the two of them ate.
07Jdg 19:9 The man got up to go with his concubine and his servant, when his father-in-law, the girl's father, said to him, "Look, night is coming. Please spend the night. See, the day is almost over. Spend the night here, enjoy yourself, then you can get up early tomorrow for your journey and go home."
07Jdg 19:10 But the man was unwilling to spend the night. He got up, departed, and arrived opposite Jebus (that is, Jerusalem). The man had his two saddled donkeys and his concubine with him.
07Jdg 19:11 When they were near Jebus and the day was almost gone, the servant said to his master, "Please, why not let us stop at this Jebusite city and spend the night here?"
07Jdg 19:12 But his master replied to him, "We will not stop at a foreign city where there are no Israelites. Let's move on to Gibeah."
07Jdg 19:13 "Come on," he said, "let's try to reach one of these places and spend the night in Gibeah or Ramah."
07Jdg 19:14 So they continued on their journey, and the sun set as they neared Gibeah in Benjamin.
07Jdg 19:15 They stopped to go in and spend the night in Gibeah. The Levite went in and sat down in the city square, but no one took them into their home to spend the night.
07Jdg 19:16 In the evening, an old man came in from his work in the field. He was from the hill country of Ephraim but was residing in Gibeah, and the men of that place were Benjaminites.
07Jdg 19:17 When he looked up and saw the traveler in the city square, the old man asked, "Where are you going, and where do you come from?"
07Jdg 19:18 He answered him, "We're traveling from Bethlehem in Judah to the remote hill country of Ephraim, where I am from. I went to Bethlehem in Judah, and now I'm going to the house of the LORD. No one has taken me into his home,
07Jdg 19:19 although we have both straw and feed for our donkeys, and bread and wine for me, your female servant, and the young man with your servant. There is nothing we lack."
07Jdg 19:20 "Peace to you," said the old man. "I'll take care of everything you need. Only don't spend the night in the square."
07Jdg 19:21 So he brought him to his house and fed the donkeys. Then they washed their feet and ate and drank.
07Jdg 19:22 While they were enjoying themselves, all of a sudden, perverted men of the city surrounded the house and beat on the door. They said to the old man who was the owner of the house, "Bring out the man who came to your house so we can have sex with him!"
07Jdg 19:23 The owner of the house went out and said to them, "No, don't do [this] evil, my brothers. After all, this man has come into my house. Don't do this horrible thing.
07Jdg 19:24 Here, let me bring out my virgin daughter and the man's concubine now. Use them and do whatever you want to them. But don't do this horrible thing to this man."
07Jdg 19:25 But the men would not listen to him, so the man seized his concubine and took her outside to them. They raped her and abused her all night until morning. At daybreak they let her go.
07Jdg 19:26 Early that morning, the woman made her way back, and as it was getting light, she collapsed at the doorway of the man's house where her master was.
07Jdg 19:27 When her master got up in the morning, opened the doors of the house, and went out to leave on his journey, there was the woman, his concubine, collapsed near the doorway of the house with her hands on the threshold.
07Jdg 19:28 "Get up," he told her. "Let's go." But there was no response. So the man put her on his donkey and set out for home.
07Jdg 19:29 When he entered his house, he picked up a knife, took hold of his concubine, cut her into 12 pieces, limb by limb, and sent her throughout the territory of Israel.
07Jdg 19:30 Everyone who saw it said, "Nothing like this has ever happened or been seen since the day the Israelites came out of the land of Egypt to this day. Think it over, discuss it, and speak up!"
07Jdg 20:1 All the Israelites from Dan to Beer-sheba and from the land of Gilead came out, and the community assembled as one body before the LORD at Mizpah.
07Jdg 20:2 The leaders of all the people and of all the tribes of Israel presented themselves in the assembly of God's people: 400,000 armed foot-soldiers.
07Jdg 20:3 The Benjaminites heard that the Israelites had gone up to Mizpah. The Israelites asked, "Tell us, how did this outrage occur?"
07Jdg 20:4 The Levite, the husband of the murdered woman, answered: "I went to Gibeah in Benjamin with my concubine to spend the night.
07Jdg 20:5 Citizens of Gibeah ganged up on me and surrounded the house at night. They intended to kill me, but they raped my concubine, and she died.
07Jdg 20:6 Then I took my concubine and cut her in pieces, and sent her throughout Israel's territory, because they committed a horrible shame in Israel.
07Jdg 20:7 Look, all of you are Israelites. Give your judgment and verdict here [and now]."
07Jdg 20:8 Then all the people stood united and said, "None of us will go to his tent or return to his house.
07Jdg 20:9 Now this is what we will do to Gibeah: we will go against it by lot.
07Jdg 20:10 We will take 10 men out of every 100 from all the tribes of Israel, and 100 out of every 1,000, and 1,000 out of every 10,000 to get provisions for the people when they go to Gibeah in Benjamin to punish them for all the horror they did in Israel."
07Jdg 20:11 So all the men of Israel gathered united against the city.
07Jdg 20:12 Then the tribes of Israel sent men throughout the tribe of Benjamin, saying, "What is this outrage that has occurred among you?
07Jdg 20:13 Hand over the perverted men in Gibeah so we can put them to death and eradicate evil from Israel." But the Benjaminites would not obey their fellow Israelites.
07Jdg 20:14 Instead, the Benjaminites gathered together from their cities to Gibeah to go out and fight against the Israelites.
07Jdg 20:15 On that day the Benjaminites rallied 26,000 armed men from their cities, besides 700 choice men rallied by the inhabitants of Gibeah.
07Jdg 20:16 There were 700 choice men who were left-handed among all these people; all could sling a stone at a hair and not miss.
07Jdg 20:17 The Israelites, apart from Benjamin, rallied 400,000 armed men, every one an experienced warrior.
07Jdg 20:18 They set out, went to Bethel, and inquired of God. The Israelites asked, "Who is to go first to fight for us against the Benjaminites?" And the LORD answered, "Judah will be first."
07Jdg 20:19 In the morning, the Israelites set out and camped near Gibeah.
07Jdg 20:20 The men of Israel went out to fight against Benjamin and took their battle positions against Gibeah.
07Jdg 20:21 The Benjaminites came out of Gibeah and slaughtered 22,000 men of Israel on the field that day.
07Jdg 20:22 But the Israelite army rallied and again took their battle positions in the same place where they positioned themselves on the first day.
07Jdg 20:23 They went up, wept before the LORD until evening, and inquired of Him: "Should we again fight against our brothers the Benjaminites?" And the LORD answered: "Fight against them."
07Jdg 20:24 On the second day the Israelites advanced against the Benjaminites.
07Jdg 20:25 That same day the Benjaminites came out from Gibeah to meet them and slaughtered an additional 18,000 Israelites on the field; all were armed men.
07Jdg 20:26 The whole Israelite army went to Bethel where they wept and sat before the LORD. They fasted that day until evening and offered burnt offerings and fellowship offerings to the LORD.
07Jdg 20:27 Then the Israelites inquired of the LORD. In those days, the ark of the covenant of God was there,
07Jdg 20:28 and Phinehas son of Eleazar, son of Aaron, was serving before it. The Israelites asked: "Should we again fight against our brothers the Benjaminites or should we stop?" The LORD answered: "Fight, because I will hand them over to you tomorrow."
07Jdg 20:29 So Israel set up an ambush around Gibeah.
07Jdg 20:30 On the third day the Israelites fought against the Benjaminites and took their battle positions against Gibeah as before.
07Jdg 20:31 Then the Benjaminites came out against the people and were drawn away from the city. They began to attack the people as before, killing about 30 men of Israel on the highways, one of which goes up to Bethel and the other to Gibeah through the open country.
07Jdg 20:32 The Benjaminites said, "We are defeating them as before." But the Israelites said, "Let's flee and draw them away from the city to the highways."
07Jdg 20:33 So all the men of Israel got up from their places and took their battle positions at Baal-tamar, while the Israelites in ambush charged out of their places west of Geba.
07Jdg 20:34 Then 10,000 choice men from all Israel made a frontal assault against Gibeah, and the battle was fierce, but the Benjaminites did not know that disaster was about to strike them.
07Jdg 20:35 The LORD defeated Benjamin in the presence of Israel, and on that day the Israelites slaughtered 25,100 men of Benjamin; all were armed men.
07Jdg 20:36 Then the Benjaminites realized they had been defeated. The men of Israel had retreated before Benjamin, because they were confident in the ambush they had set against Gibeah.
07Jdg 20:37 The men in ambush had rushed quickly against Gibeah; they advanced and put the whole city to the sword.
07Jdg 20:38 The men of Israel had a prearranged signal with the men in ambush: when they sent up a great cloud of smoke from the city,
07Jdg 20:39 the men of Israel would return to the battle. When Benjamin had begun to strike them down, killing about 30 men of Israel, they said, "They're defeated before us, just as they were in the first battle."
07Jdg 20:40 But when the column of smoke began to go up from the city, Benjamin looked behind them, and the whole city was going up in smoke.
07Jdg 20:41 Then the men of Israel returned, and the men of Benjamin were terrified when they realized that disaster had struck them.
07Jdg 20:42 They retreated before the men of Israel toward the wilderness, but the battle overtook them, and those who came out of the cities slaughtered those between them.
07Jdg 20:43 They surrounded the Benjaminites, pursued them, and easily overtook them near Gibeah toward the east.
07Jdg 20:44 There were 18,000 men who died from Benjamin; all were warriors.
07Jdg 20:45 Then Benjamin turned and fled toward the wilderness to the rock of Rimmon, and Israel killed 5,000 men on the highways. They overtook them at Gidom and struck 2,000 more dead.
07Jdg 20:46 All the Benjaminites who died that day were 25,000 armed men; all were warriors.
07Jdg 20:47 But 600 men escaped into the wilderness to the rock of Rimmon and stayed there four months.
07Jdg 20:48 The men of Israel turned back against the [other] Benjaminites and killed them with their swords-- the entire city, the animals, and everything that remained. They also burned down all the cities that remained.
07Jdg 21:1 The men of Israel had sworn an oath at Mizpah: "None of us will give his daughter to a Benjaminite in marriage."
07Jdg 21:2 So the people went to Bethel and sat there before God until evening. They wept loudly and bitterly,
07Jdg 21:3 and cried out, "Why, LORD God of Israel, has it occurred that one tribe is [missing] in Israel today?"
07Jdg 21:4 The next day the people got up early, built an altar there, and offered burnt offerings and fellowship offerings.
07Jdg 21:5 The Israelites asked, "Who of all the tribes of Israel didn't come to the LORD with the assembly?" For a great oath had been taken that anyone who had not come to the LORD at Mizpah would certainly be put to death.
07Jdg 21:6 But the Israelites had compassion on their brothers, the Benjaminites, and said, "Today a tribe has been cut off from Israel.
07Jdg 21:7 What should we do about wives for the survivors? We've sworn to the LORD not to give them any of our daughters as wives."
07Jdg 21:8 They asked, "Which city among the tribes of Israel didn't come to the LORD at Mizpah?" It turned out that no one from Jabesh-gilead had come to the camp and the assembly.
07Jdg 21:9 For when the people were counted, no one was there from the inhabitants of Jabesh-gilead.
07Jdg 21:10 The congregation sent 12,000 brave warriors there and commanded them: "Go and kill the inhabitants of Jabesh-gilead with the sword, including women and children.
07Jdg 21:11 This is what you should do: Completely destroy every male, as well as every female who has slept with a man."
07Jdg 21:12 They found among the inhabitants of Jabesh-gilead 400 young virgins, who had not had sexual relations with a man, and they brought them to the camp at Shiloh in the land of Canaan.
07Jdg 21:13 The whole congregation sent a message of peace to the Benjaminites who were at the rock of Rimmon.
07Jdg 21:14 Benjamin returned at that time, and Israel gave them the women they had kept alive from Jabesh-gilead. But there were not enough for them.
07Jdg 21:15 The people had compassion on Benjamin, because the LORD had made this gap in the tribes of Israel.
07Jdg 21:16 The elders of the congregation said, "What should we do about wives for those who are left, since the women of Benjamin have been destroyed?"
07Jdg 21:17 They said, "There must be heirs for the survivors of Benjamin, so that a tribe of Israel will not be wiped out.
07Jdg 21:18 But we can't give them our daughters as wives." For the Israelites had sworn: "Anyone who gives a wife to a Benjaminite is cursed."
07Jdg 21:19 They also said, "Look, there's an annual festival to the LORD in Shiloh, which is north of Bethel, east of the highway that goes up from Bethel to Shechem, and south of Lebonah."
07Jdg 21:20 Then they commanded the Benjaminites: "Go and hide in the vineyards.
07Jdg 21:21 Watch, and when you see the young women of Shiloh come out to perform the dances, each of you leave the vineyards and catch a wife for yourself from the young women of Shiloh, and go to the land of Benjamin.
07Jdg 21:22 When their fathers or brothers come to us and protest, we will tell them, 'Show favor to them, since we did not get enough wives for each of them in the battle. You didn't actually give [the women] to them, so you are not guilty [of breaking your oath].'"
07Jdg 21:23 The Benjaminites did this and took the number of women they needed from the dancers they caught. They went back to their own inheritance, rebuilt their cities, and lived in them.
07Jdg 21:24 At that time, each of the Israelites returned from there to his own tribe and family. Each returned from there to his own inheritance.
07Jdg 21:25 In those days there was no king in Israel; everyone did whatever he wanted.
