102Sm 1:1 After the death of Saul, David returned from defeating the Amalekites and stayed at Ziklag two days.
102Sm 1:2 On the third day a man with torn clothes and dust on his head came from Saul's camp. When he came to David, he fell to the ground and paid homage.
102Sm 1:3 David asked him, "Where have you come from?" He replied to him, "I've escaped from the Israelite camp."
102Sm 1:4 "What was the outcome? Tell me," David asked him. "The troops fled from the battle," he answered. "Many of the troops have fallen and are dead. Also, Saul and his son Jonathan are dead."
102Sm 1:5 David asked the young man who had brought him the report, "How do you know Saul and his son Jonathan are dead?"
102Sm 1:6 "I happened to be on Mount Gilboa," he replied, "and there was Saul, leaning on his spear. At that very moment the chariots and the cavalry were closing in on him.
102Sm 1:7 When he turned around and saw me, he called out to me, so I answered: I'm at your service.
102Sm 1:8 He asked me, 'Who are you?' I told him: I'm an Amalekite.
102Sm 1:9 Then he begged me, 'Stand over me and kill me, for I'm mortally wounded, but my life still lingers.'
102Sm 1:10 So I stood over him and killed him because I knew that after he had fallen he couldn't survive. I took the crown that was on his head and the armband that was on his arm, and I've brought them here to my lord."
102Sm 1:11 Then David took hold of his clothes and tore them, and all the men with him did the same.
102Sm 1:12 They mourned, wept, and fasted until the evening for those who died by the sword-- for Saul, his son Jonathan, the LORD's people, and the house of Israel.
102Sm 1:13 David inquired of the young man who had brought him the report, "Where are you from?" "I'm the son of a foreigner" he said. "I'm an Amalekite."
102Sm 1:14 David questioned him, "How is it that you were not afraid to lift your hand to destroy the LORD's anointed?"
102Sm 1:15 Then David summoned one of his servants and said, "Come here and kill him!" The servant struck him, and he died.
102Sm 1:16 For David had said to the Amalekite, "Your blood is on your own head because your own mouth testified against you by saying, 'I killed the LORD's anointed.'"
102Sm 1:17 David sang the following lament for Saul and his son Jonathan,
102Sm 1:18 and he ordered that the Judahites be taught [The Song of] the Bow. It is written in the Book of Jashar:
102Sm 1:19 The splendor of Israel lies slain on your heights. How the mighty have fallen!
102Sm 1:20 Do not tell it in Gath, don't announce it in the streets of Ashkelon, or the daughters of the Philistines will rejoice, and the daughters of the uncircumcised will gloat.
102Sm 1:21 Mountains of Gilboa, let no dew or rain be on you, or fields of offerings, for there the shield of the mighty was defiled-- the shield of Saul, no longer anointed with oil.
102Sm 1:22 Jonathan's bow never retreated, Saul's sword never returned unstained, from the blood of the slain, from the bodies of the mighty.
102Sm 1:23 Saul and Jonathan, loved and delightful, they were not parted in life or in death. They were swifter than eagles, stronger than lions.
102Sm 1:24 Daughters of Israel, weep for Saul, who clothed you in scarlet, with luxurious things, who decked your garments with gold ornaments.
102Sm 1:25 How the mighty have fallen in the thick of battle! Jonathan [lies] slain on your heights.
102Sm 1:26 I grieve for you, Jonathan my brother. You were such a friend to me. Your love for me was more wonderful than the love of a woman [for me].
102Sm 1:27 How the mighty have fallen and the weapons of war have perished!
102Sm 2:1 Some time later, David inquired of the LORD: "Should I go to one of the towns of Judah?" The LORD answered him, "Go." Then David asked, "Where should I go?" "To Hebron," the LORD replied.
102Sm 2:2 So David went there with his two wives, Ahinoam the Jezreelite and Abigail, the widow of Nabal the Carmelite.
102Sm 2:3 In addition, David brought the men who were with him, each one with his household, and they settled in the towns near Hebron.
102Sm 2:4 Then the men of Judah came, and there they anointed David king over the house of Judah. They told David: "It was the men of Jabesh-gilead who buried Saul."
102Sm 2:5 David sent messengers to the men of Jabesh-gilead and said to them, "The LORD bless you, because you have shown this special kindness to Saul your lord when you buried him.
102Sm 2:6 Now, may the LORD show special kindness and faithfulness to you, and I will also show the same goodness to you because you have done this deed.
102Sm 2:7 Therefore, be strong and courageous, for though Saul your lord is dead, the house of Judah has anointed me king over them."
102Sm 2:8 Abner son of Ner, commander of Saul's army, took Saul's son Ish-boshethand moved him to Mahanaim.
102Sm 2:9 He made him king over Gilead, Asher, Jezreel, Ephraim, Benjamin-- over all Israel.
102Sm 2:10 Saul's son Ish-bosheth was 40 years old when he began his reign over Israel; he ruled for two years. The house of Judah, however, followed David.
102Sm 2:11 The length of time that David was king in Hebron over the house of Judah was seven years and six months.
102Sm 2:12 Abner son of Ner and soldiers of Ish-bosheth son of Saul marched out from Mahanaim to Gibeon.
102Sm 2:13 So Joab son of Zeruiah and David's soldiers marched out and met them by the pool of Gibeon. The two groups took up positions on opposite sides of the pool.
102Sm 2:14 Then Abner said to Joab, "Let's have the young men get up and compete in front of us." "Let them get up," Joab replied.
102Sm 2:15 So they got up and were counted off-- 12 for Benjamin and Ish-bosheth son of Saul, and 12 from David's soldiers.
102Sm 2:16 Then each man grabbed his opponent by the head and [thrust] his sword into his opponent's side so that they all died together. So this place, which is in Gibeon, is named Field of Blades.
102Sm 2:17 The battle that day was extremely fierce, and Abner and the men of Israel were defeated by David's soldiers.
102Sm 2:18 The three sons of Zeruiah were there: Joab, Abishai, and Asahel. Asahel was a fast runner, like one of the wild gazelles.
102Sm 2:19 He chased Abner and did not turn to the right or the left in his pursuit of him.
102Sm 2:20 Abner glanced back and said, "Is that you, Asahel?" "Yes it is," Asahel replied.
102Sm 2:21 Abner said to him, "Turn to your right or left, seize one of the young soldiers, and take whatever you can get from him." But Asahel would not stop chasing him.
102Sm 2:22 Once again, Abner warned Asahel, "Stop chasing me. Why should I strike you to the ground? How could I ever look your brother Joab in the face?"
102Sm 2:23 But Asahel refused to turn away, so Abner hit him in the stomach with the end of his spear. The spear went through his body, and he fell and died right there. When all who came to the place where Asahel had fallen and died, they stopped,
102Sm 2:24 but Joab and Abishai pursued Abner. By sunset, they had gone as far as the hill of Ammah, which is opposite Giah on the way to the wilderness of Gibeon.
102Sm 2:25 The Benjaminites rallied to Abner; they formed a single unit and took their stand on top of a hill.
102Sm 2:26 Then Abner called out to Joab: "Must the sword devour forever? Don't you realize this will only end in bitterness? How long before you tell the troops to stop pursuing their brothers?"
102Sm 2:27 "As God lives," Joab replied, "if you had not spoken up, the troops wouldn't have stopped pursuing their brothers until morning."
102Sm 2:28 Then Joab blew the ram's horn, and all the troops stopped; they no longer pursued Israel or continued to fight.
102Sm 2:29 So Abner and his men marched through the Arabah all that night. They crossed the Jordan, marched all morning, and arrived at Mahanaim.
102Sm 2:30 When Joab had turned back from pursuing Abner, he gathered all the troops. In addition to Asahel, 19 of David's soldiers were missing,
102Sm 2:31 but they had killed 360 of the Benjaminites and Abner's men.
102Sm 2:32 Afterwards, they carried Asahel to his father's tomb in Bethlehem and buried him. Then Joab and his men marched all night and reached Hebron at dawn.
102Sm 3:1 The war between the house of Saul and the house of David was long and drawn out, with David growing stronger and the house of Saul becoming weaker.
102Sm 3:2 Sons were born to David in Hebron: his firstborn was Amnon, by Ahinoam the Jezreelite;
102Sm 3:3 his second was Chileab, by Abigail, the widow of Nabal the Carmelite; the third was Absalom, son of Maacah the daughter of King Talmai of Geshur;
102Sm 3:4 the fourth was Adonijah, son of Haggith; the fifth was Shephatiah, son of Abital;
102Sm 3:5 the sixth was Ithream, by David's wife Eglah. These were born to David in Hebron.
102Sm 3:6 During the war between the house of Saul and the house of David, Abner kept acquiring more power in the house of Saul.
102Sm 3:7 Now Saul had a concubine whose name was Rizpah daughter of Aiah, and Ish-bosheth questioned Abner, "Why did you sleep with my father's concubine?"
102Sm 3:8 Abner was very angry about Ish-bosheth's accusation. "Am I a dog's head who belongs to Judah?" he asked. "All this time I've been loyal to the house of your father Saul, to his brothers, and to his friends and haven't handed you over to David, but now you accuse me of wrongdoing with this woman!
102Sm 3:9 May God punish Abner and do so severely if I don't do for David what the LORD swore to him:
102Sm 3:10 to transfer the kingdom from the house of Saul and establish the throne of David over Israel and Judah from Dan to Beer-sheba."
102Sm 3:11 Ish-bosheth could not answer Abner because he was afraid of him.
102Sm 3:12 Abner sent messengers as his representatives to say to David, "Whose land is it? Make your covenant with me, and you can be certain I am on your side to hand all Israel over to you."
102Sm 3:13 David replied, "Good, I will make a covenant with you. However, there's one thing I require of you: Do not appear before me unless you bring Saul's daughter Michal here when you come to see me."
102Sm 3:14 Then David sent messengers to say to Ish-bosheth son of Saul, "Give me back my wife, Michal. I was engaged to her for the price of 100 Philistine foreskins."
102Sm 3:15 So Ish-bosheth sent someone to take her away from her husband, Paltiel son of Laish.
102Sm 3:16 Her husband followed her, weeping all the way to Bahurim. Abner said to him, "Go back." So he went back.
102Sm 3:17 Abner conferred with the elders of Israel: "In the past you wanted David to be king over you.
102Sm 3:18 Now take action, because the LORD has spoken concerning David: 'Through My servant David I will save My people Israel from the power of the Philistines and the power of all Israel's enemies.'"
102Sm 3:19 Abner also informed the Benjaminites and went to Hebron to inform David about all that was agreed on by Israel and the whole house of Benjamin.
102Sm 3:20 When Abner and 20 men came to David at Hebron, David held a banquet for him and his men.
102Sm 3:21 Abner said to David, "Let me now go and I will gather all Israel to my lord the king. They will make a covenant with you, and you will rule over all you desire." So David dismissed Abner, and he went in peace.
102Sm 3:22 Just then David's soldiers and Joab returned from a raid and brought a large amount of plundered goods with them. Abner was not with David in Hebron because David had dismissed him, and he had gone in peace.
102Sm 3:23 When Joab and all his army arrived, Joab was informed, "Abner son of Ner came to see the king, the king dismissed him, and he went in peace."
102Sm 3:24 Joab went to the king and said, "What have you done? Look here, Abner came to you. Why did you dismiss him? Now he's getting away.
102Sm 3:25 You know that Abner son of Ner came to deceive you and to find out about your activities and everything you're doing."
102Sm 3:26 Then Joab left David and sent messengers after Abner. They brought him back from the well of Sirah, but David was unaware of it.
102Sm 3:27 When Abner returned to Hebron, Joab pulled him aside to the middle of the gateway, as if to speak to him privately, and there Joab stabbed him in the stomach. So Abner died in revenge for the death of Asahel, Joab's brother.
102Sm 3:28 David heard [about it] later and said: "I and my kingdom are forever innocent before the LORD concerning the blood of Abner son of Ner.
102Sm 3:29 May it hang over Joab's head and his father's whole house, and may the house of Joab never be without someone who has an infection or leprosy or a man who can only work a spindle or someone who falls by the sword or starves."
102Sm 3:30 Joab and his brother Abishai killed Abner because he had put their brother Asahel to death in the battle at Gibeon.
102Sm 3:31 David then ordered Joab and all the people who were with him, "Tear your clothes, put on sackcloth, and mourn over Abner." And King David walked behind the funeral procession.
102Sm 3:32 When they buried Abner in Hebron, the king wept aloud at Abner's tomb. All the people wept,
102Sm 3:33 and the king sang a lament for Abner: Should Abner die as a fool dies?
102Sm 3:34 Your hands were not bound, your feet not placed in bronze [shackles]. You fell like one who falls victim to criminals. And all the people wept over him even more.
102Sm 3:35 Then they came to urge David to eat bread while it was still day, but David took an oath: "May God punish me and do so severely if I taste bread or anything else before sunset!"
102Sm 3:36 All the people took note of this, and it pleased them. In fact, everything the king did pleased them.
102Sm 3:37 On that day all the troops and all Israel were convinced that the king had no part in the killing of Abner son of Ner.
102Sm 3:38 Then the king said to his soldiers, "You must know that a great leader has fallen in Israel today.
102Sm 3:39 As for me, even though I am the anointed king, I have little power today. These men, the sons of Zeruiah, are too fierce for me. May the LORD repay the evildoer according to his evil!"
102Sm 4:1 When Saul's son [Ish-bosheth] heard that Abner had died in Hebron, his courage failed, and all Israel was dismayed.
102Sm 4:2 Saul's son had two men who were leaders of raiding parties: one named Baanah and the other Rechab, sons of Rimmon the Beerothite of the Benjaminites. Beeroth is also considered part of Benjamin,
102Sm 4:3 and the Beerothites fled to Gittaim and still live there as aliens to this very day.
102Sm 4:4 Saul's son Jonathan had a son whose feet were crippled. He was five years old when the report about Saul and Jonathan came from Jezreel. His nurse picked him up and fled, but as she was hurrying to flee, he fell and became lame. His name was Mephibosheth.
102Sm 4:5 Rechab and Baanah, the sons of Rimmon the Beerothite, set out and arrived at Ish-bosheth's house during the heat of the day while the king was taking his midday nap.
102Sm 4:6 They entered the interior of the house as if to get wheat and stabbed him in the stomach. Then Rechab and his brother Baanah escaped.
102Sm 4:7 They had entered the house while Ish-bosheth was lying on his bed in his bedroom and stabbed and killed him. Then they beheaded him, took his head, and traveled by way of the Arabah all night.
102Sm 4:8 They brought Ish-bosheth's head to David at Hebron and said to the king, "Here's the head of Ish-bosheth son of Saul, your enemy who intended to take your life. Today the LORD has granted vengeance to my lord the king against Saul and his offspring."
102Sm 4:9 But David answered Rechab and his brother Baanah, sons of Rimmon the Beerothite, "As surely as the LORD lives, [the One] who has redeemed my life from every distress,
102Sm 4:10 when the person told me, 'Look, Saul is dead,' he thought he was a bearer of good news, but I seized him and put him to death at Ziklag. That was my reward to him for his news!
102Sm 4:11 How much more when wicked men kill a righteous man in his own house on his own bed! So now, should I not require his blood from your hands and wipe you off the earth?"
102Sm 4:12 So David gave orders to the young men, and they killed Rechab and Baanah. They cut off their hands and feet and hung [their bodies] by the pool in Hebron, but they took Ish-bosheth's head and buried it in Abner's tomb in Hebron.
102Sm 5:1 All the tribes of Israel came to David at Hebron and said, "Here we are, your own flesh and blood.
102Sm 5:2 Even while Saul was king over us, you were the one who led us out [to battle] and brought us back. The LORD also said to you, 'You will shepherd My people Israel and be ruler over Israel.'"
102Sm 5:3 So all the elders of Israel came to the king at Hebron. King David made a covenant with them at Hebron in the LORD's presence, and they anointed David king over Israel.
102Sm 5:4 David was 30 years old when he began his reign; he reigned 40 years.
102Sm 5:5 In Hebron he reigned over Judah seven years and six months, and in Jerusalem he reigned 33 years over all Israel and Judah.
102Sm 5:6 The king and his men marched to Jerusalem against the Jebusites who inhabited the land. The Jebusites had said to David: "You will never get in here. Even the blind and lame can repel you," thinking, "David can't get in here."
102Sm 5:7 Yet David did capture the stronghold of Zion, the city of David.
102Sm 5:8 He said that day, "Whoever attacks the Jebusites must go through the water shaft to reach the lame and the blind who are despised by David." For this reason it is said, "The blind and the lame will never enter the house."
102Sm 5:9 David took up residence in the stronghold, which he named the city of David. He built it up all the way around from the supporting terraces inward.
102Sm 5:10 David became more and more powerful, and the LORD God of Hosts was with him.
102Sm 5:11 King Hiram of Tyre sent envoys to David; [he also sent] cedar logs, carpenters, and stonemasons, and they built a palace for David.
102Sm 5:12 Then David knew that the LORD had established him as king over Israel and had exalted his kingdom for the sake of His people Israel.
102Sm 5:13 After he arrived from Hebron, David took more concubines and wives in Jerusalem, and more sons and daughters were born to him.
102Sm 5:14 These are the names of those born to him in Jerusalem: Shammua, Shobab, Nathan, Solomon,
102Sm 5:15 Ibhar, Elishua, Nepheg, Japhia,
102Sm 5:16 Elishama, Eliada, and Eliphelet.
102Sm 5:17 When the Philistines heard that David had been anointed king over Israel, they all went in search of David, but he heard about it and went down to the stronghold.
102Sm 5:18 So the Philistines came and spread out in the Valley of Rephaim.
102Sm 5:19 Then David inquired of the LORD: "Should I go to war against the Philistines? Will you hand them over to me?" The LORD replied to David, "Go, for I will certainly hand the Philistines over to you."
102Sm 5:20 So David went to Baal-perazim and defeated them there and said, "Like a bursting flood, the LORD has burst out against my enemies before me." Therefore, he named that place the Lord Bursts Out.
102Sm 5:21 The Philistines abandoned their idols there, and David and his men carried them off.
102Sm 5:22 The Philistines came up again and spread out in the Valley of Rephaim.
102Sm 5:23 So David inquired of the Lord, and He answered, "Do not make a frontal assault. Circle around behind them and attack them opposite the balsam trees.
102Sm 5:24 When you hear the sound of marching in the tops of the balsam trees, act decisively, for then the LORD will have marched out ahead of you to attack the camp of the Philistines."
102Sm 5:25 So David did exactly as the LORD commanded him, and he struck down the Philistines all the way from Geba to Gezer.
102Sm 6:1 David again assembled all the choice men in Israel, 30,000.
102Sm 6:2 He and all his troops set out to bring the ark of God from Baale-judah.The ark is called by the Name, the name of the LORD of Hosts who dwells [between] the cherubim.
102Sm 6:3 They set the ark of God on a new cart and transported it from Abinadab's house, which was on the hill. Uzzah and Ahio, sons of Abinadab, were guiding the cart
102Sm 6:4 and brought it with the ark of God from Abinadab's house on the hill. Ahio walked in front of the ark.
102Sm 6:5 David and the whole house of Israel were celebrating before the LORD with all [kinds of] fir wood [instruments], lyres, harps, tambourines, sistrums, and cymbals.
102Sm 6:6 When they came to Nacon's threshing floor, Uzzah reached out to the ark of God and took hold of it, because the oxen had stumbled.
102Sm 6:7 Then the LORD's anger burned against Uzzah, and God struck him dead on the spot for his irreverence, and he died there next to the ark of God.
102Sm 6:8 David was angry because of the LORD's outburst against Uzzah, so he named that place an Outburst Against Uzzah, as it is today.
102Sm 6:9 David feared the LORD that day and said, "How can the ark of the LORD ever come to me?"
102Sm 6:10 So he was not willing to move the ark of the LORD to the city of David; instead, he took it to the house of Obed-edom the Gittite.
102Sm 6:11 The ark of the LORD remained in his house three months, and the LORD blessed Obed-edom and his whole family.
102Sm 6:12 It was reported to King David: "The LORD has blessed Obed-edom's family and all that belongs to him because of the ark of God." So David went and had the ark of God brought up from Obed-edom's house to the city of David with rejoicing.
102Sm 6:13 When those carrying the ark of the LORD advanced six steps, he sacrificed an ox and a fattened calf.
102Sm 6:14 David was dancing with all his might before the LORD wearing a linen ephod.
102Sm 6:15 He and the whole house of Israel were bringing up the ark of the LORD with shouts and the sound of the ram's horn.
102Sm 6:16 As the ark of the LORD was entering the city of David, Saul's daughter Michal looked down from the window and saw King David leaping and dancing before the LORD, and she despised him in her heart.
102Sm 6:17 They brought the ark of the LORD and set it in its place inside the tent David had set up for it. Then David offered burnt offerings and fellowship offerings in the LORD's presence.
102Sm 6:18 When David had finished offering the burnt offering and the fellowship offerings, he blessed the people in the name of the LORD of Hosts.
102Sm 6:19 Then he distributed a loaf of bread, a date cake, and a raisin cake to each one of the whole multitude of the people of Israel, both men and women. Then all the people left, each to his own home.
102Sm 6:20 When David returned [home] to bless his household, Saul's daughter Michal came out to meet him. "How the king of Israel honored himself today!" she said. "He exposed himself today in the sight of the slave girls of his subjects like a vulgar person would expose himself."
102Sm 6:21 David replied to Michal, "I was dancing before the LORD who chose me over your father and his whole family to appoint me ruler over the LORD's people Israel. I will celebrate before the LORD,
102Sm 6:22 and I will humble myself even more and humiliate myself.I will be honored by the slave girls you spoke about."
102Sm 6:23 And Saul's daughter Michal had no child to the day of her death.
102Sm 7:1 When the king had settled into his palace and the LORD had given him rest on every side from all his enemies,
102Sm 7:2 the king said to Nathan the prophet, "Look, I am living in a cedar house while the ark of God sits inside tent curtains."
102Sm 7:3 So Nathan told the king, "Go and do all that is on your heart, for the LORD is with you."
102Sm 7:4 But that night the word of the LORD came to Nathan:
102Sm 7:5 "Go to My servant David and say, 'This is what the LORD says: Are you to build a house for Me to live in?
102Sm 7:6 From the time I brought the Israelites out of Egypt until today I have not lived in a house; instead, I have been moving around with the tabernacle tent.
102Sm 7:7 In all My journeys with all the Israelites, have I ever asked anyone among the tribes of Israel, whom I commanded to shepherd My people Israel: Why haven't you built Me a house of cedar?'
102Sm 7:8 "Now this is what you are to say to My servant David: 'This is what the LORD of Hosts says: I took you from the pasture and from following the sheep to be ruler over My people Israel.
102Sm 7:9 I have been with you wherever you have gone, and I have destroyed all your enemies before you. I will make a name for you like that of the greatest in the land.
102Sm 7:10 I will establish a place for My people Israel and plant them, so that they may live there and not be disturbed again. Evildoers will not afflict them as they have done
102Sm 7:11 ever since the day I ordered judges to be over My people Israel. I will give you rest from all your enemies. " 'The LORD declares to you: The LORD Himself will make a house for you.
102Sm 7:12 When your time comes and you rest with your fathers, I will raise up after you your descendant, who will come from your body, and I will establish his kingdom.
102Sm 7:13 He will build a house for My name, and I will establish the throne of his kingdom forever.
102Sm 7:14 I will be a father to him, and he will be a son to Me. When he does wrong, I will discipline him with a human rod and with blows from others.
102Sm 7:15 But My faithful love will never leave him as I removed it from Saul; I removed him from your way.
102Sm 7:16 Your house and kingdom will endure before Me forever, and your throne will be established forever.'"
102Sm 7:17 Nathan spoke all these words and this entire vision to David.
102Sm 7:18 Then King David went in, sat in the LORD's presence, and said, "Who am I, Lord God, and what is my house that You have brought me this far?
102Sm 7:19 What You have done so far was a little thing to You, Lord God, for You have also spoken about Your servant's house in the distant future. And this is a revelation for mankind, Lord God.
102Sm 7:20 What more can David say to You? You know Your servant, Lord God.
102Sm 7:21 Because of Your word and according to Your will, You have revealed all these great things to Your servant.
102Sm 7:22 "This is why You are great, Lord God. There is no one like You, and there is no God besides You, as all we have heard confirms.
102Sm 7:23 And who is like Your people Israel? God came to one nation on earth in order to redeem a people for Himself, to make a name for Himself, and to perform for them great and awesome acts, driving out nations and their gods before Your people You redeemed for Yourself from Egypt.
102Sm 7:24 You established Your people Israel Your own people forever, and You, LORD, have become their God.
102Sm 7:25 "Now, LORD God, fulfill the promise forever that You have made to Your servant and his house. Do as You have promised,
102Sm 7:26 so that Your name will be exalted forever, when it is said, 'The LORD of Hosts is God over Israel.' The house of Your servant David will be established before You
102Sm 7:27 since You, LORD of Hosts, God of Israel, have revealed this to Your servant when You said, 'I will build a house for you.' Therefore, Your servant has found the courage to pray this prayer to You.
102Sm 7:28 Lord God, You are God; Your words are true, and You have promised this grace to Your servant.
102Sm 7:29 Now, please bless Your servant's house so that it will continue before You forever. For You, Lord God, have spoken, and with Your blessing Your servant's house will be blessed forever."
102Sm 8:1 After this, David defeated the Philistines, subdued them, and took Metheg-ammah from Philistine control.
102Sm 8:2 He also defeated the Moabites, and after making them lie down on the ground, he measured them off with a cord. He measured every two cord lengths [of those] to be put to death and one length [of those] to be kept alive. So the Moabites became David's subjects and brought tribute.
102Sm 8:3 David also defeated Hadadezer son of Rehob, king of Zobah, who went to restore his control at the Euphrates River.
102Sm 8:4 David captured 1,700 horsemen and 20,000 foot soldiers from him, and he hamstrung all the horses, and he kept 100 chariots.
102Sm 8:5 When the Arameans of Damascus came to assist King Hadadezer of Zobah, David struck down 22,000 Aramean men.
102Sm 8:6 Then he placed garrisons in Aram of Damascus, and the Arameans became David's subjects and brought tribute. The LORD made David victorious wherever he went.
102Sm 8:7 David took the gold shields of Hadadezer's officers and brought them to Jerusalem.
102Sm 8:8 King David also took huge quantities of bronze from Betah and Berothai, Hadadezer's cities.
102Sm 8:9 When King Toi of Hamath heard that David had defeated the entire army of Hadadezer,
102Sm 8:10 he sent his son Joram to King David to greet him and to congratulate him because David had fought against Hadadezer and defeated him, for Toi and Hadadezer had fought many wars. Joram had items of silver, gold, and bronze with him.
102Sm 8:11 King David also dedicated these to the LORD, along with the silver and gold he had dedicated from all the nations he had subdued--
102Sm 8:12 from Edom, Moab, the Ammonites, the Philistines, the Amalekites, and the spoil of Hadadezer son of Rehob, king of Zobah.
102Sm 8:13 David made a reputation for himself when he returned from striking down 18,000 Edomites in the Valley of Salt.
102Sm 8:14 He placed garrisons throughout Edom, and all the Edomites were subject to David. The LORD made David victorious wherever he went.
102Sm 8:15 So David reigned over all Israel, administering justice and righteousness for all his people.
102Sm 8:16 Joab son of Zeruiah was over the army; Jehoshaphat son of Ahilud was court historian;
102Sm 8:17 Zadok son of Ahitub and Ahimelech son of Abiathar were priests; Seraiah was court secretary;
102Sm 8:18 Benaiah son of Jehoiada [was over] the Cherethites and the Pelethites; and David's sons were chief officials.
102Sm 9:1 David asked, "Is there anyone remaining from Saul's family I can show kindness to because of Jonathan?"
102Sm 9:2 There was a servant of Saul's family named Ziba. They summoned him to David, and the king said to him, "Are you Ziba?" "[I am] your servant," he replied.
102Sm 9:3 So the king asked, "Is there anyone left of Saul's family I can show the kindness of God to?" Ziba said to the king, "There is still Jonathan's son who is lame in both feet."
102Sm 9:4 The king asked him, "Where is he?" Ziba answered the king, "You'll find him in Lo-debar at the house of Machir son of Ammiel."
102Sm 9:5 So King David had him brought from the house of Machir son of Ammiel in Lo-debar.
102Sm 9:6 Mephibosheth son of Jonathan son of Saul came to David, bowed down to the ground and paid homage. David said, "Mephibosheth!" "I am your servant," he replied.
102Sm 9:7 "Don't be afraid," David said to him, "since I intend to show you kindness because of your father Jonathan. I will restore to you all your grandfather Saul's fields, and you will always eat meals at my table."
102Sm 9:8 Mephibosheth bowed down and said, "What is your servant that you take an interest in a dead dog like me?"
102Sm 9:9 Then the king summoned Saul's attendant Ziba and said to him, "I have given to your master's grandson all that belonged to Saul and his family.
102Sm 9:10 You, your sons, and your servants are to work the ground for him, and you are to bring in [the crops] so your master's grandson will have food to eat. But Mephibosheth, your master's grandson, is always to eat at my table." Now Ziba had 15 sons and 20 servants.
102Sm 9:11 Ziba said to the king, "Your servant will do all my lord the king commands." So Mephibosheth ate at David's table just like one of the king's sons.
102Sm 9:12 Mephibosheth had a young son whose name was Mica. All those living in Ziba's house were Mephibosheth's servants.
102Sm 9:13 However, Mephibosheth lived in Jerusalem because he always ate at the king's table. He was lame in both feet.
102Sm 10:1 Some time later the king of the Ammonites died, and his son Hanun became king in his place.
102Sm 10:2 Then David said, "I'll show kindness to Hanun son of Nahash, just as his father showed kindness to me." So David sent his emissaries to console Hanun concerning his father. However, when they arrived in the land of the Ammonites,
102Sm 10:3 the Ammonite leaders said to Hanun their lord, "Just because David has sent men with condolences for you, do you really believe he's showing respect for your father? Instead, hasn't David sent his emissaries in order to scout out the city, spy on it, and overthrow it?"
102Sm 10:4 So Hanun took David's emissaries, shaved off half their beards, cut their clothes in half at the hips, and sent them away.
102Sm 10:5 When this was reported to David, he sent [someone] to meet them, since they were deeply humiliated. The king said, "Stay in Jericho until your beards grow back; then return."
102Sm 10:6 When the Ammonites realized they had become repulsive to David, they hired 20,000 foot soldiers from the Arameans of Beth-rehob and Zobah, 1,000 men from the king of Maacah, and 12,000 men from Tob.
102Sm 10:7 David heard about it and sent Joab and all the fighting men.
102Sm 10:8 The Ammonites marched out and lined up in battle formation at the entrance to the city gate while the Arameans of Zobah and Rehob and the men of Tob and Maacah were in the field by themselves.
102Sm 10:9 When Joab saw that there was a battle line in front of him and another behind him, he chose some men out of all the elite troops of Israel and lined up in battle formation to engage the Arameans.
102Sm 10:10 He placed the rest of the forces under the command of his brother Abishai who lined up in battle formation to engage the Ammonites.
102Sm 10:11 "If the Arameans are too strong for me," Joab said, "then you will be my help. However, if the Ammonites are too strong for you, I'll come to help you.
102Sm 10:12 Be strong! We must prove ourselves strong for our people and for the cities of our God. May the LORD's will be done."
102Sm 10:13 Joab and his troops advanced to fight against the Arameans, and they fled before him.
102Sm 10:14 When the Ammonites saw that the Arameans had fled, they too fled before Abishai and entered the city. So Joab withdrew from the attack against the Ammonites and went to Jerusalem.
102Sm 10:15 When the Arameans saw that they had been defeated by Israel, they regrouped.
102Sm 10:16 Hadadezer sent [messengers] to bring the Arameans who were across the Euphrates River, and they came to Helam with Shobach, commander of Hadadezer's army, leading them.
102Sm 10:17 When this was reported to David, he gathered all Israel, crossed the Jordan, and went to Helam. Then the Arameans lined up in formation to engage David in battle and fought against him.
102Sm 10:18 But the Arameans fled before Israel, and David killed 700 of their charioteers and 40,000 foot soldiers. He also struck down Shobach commander of their army, who died there.
102Sm 10:19 When all the kings who were Hadadezer's subjects saw that they had been defeated by Israel, they made peace with Israel and became their subjects. After this, the Arameans were afraid to ever help the Ammonites again.
102Sm 11:1 In the spring when kings march out [to war], David sent Joab with his officers and all Israel. They destroyed the Ammonites and besieged Rabbah, but David remained in Jerusalem.
102Sm 11:2 One evening David got up from his bed and strolled around on the roof of the palace. From the roof he saw a woman bathing-- a very beautiful woman.
102Sm 11:3 So David sent someone to inquire about her, and he reported, "This is Bathsheba, daughter of Eliam and wife of Uriah the Hittite."
102Sm 11:4 David sent messengers to get her, and when she came to him, he slept with her. Now she had just been purifying herself from her uncleanness. Afterwards, she returned home.
102Sm 11:5 The woman conceived and sent word to inform David: "I am pregnant."
102Sm 11:6 David sent orders to Joab: "Send me Uriah the Hittite." So Joab sent Uriah to David.
102Sm 11:7 When Uriah came to him, David asked how Joab and the troops were doing and how the war was going.
102Sm 11:8 Then he said to Uriah, "Go down to your house and wash your feet." So Uriah left the palace, and a gift from the king followed him.
102Sm 11:9 But Uriah slept at the door of the palace with all his master's servants; he did not go down to his house.
102Sm 11:10 When it was reported to David, "Uriah didn't go home," David questioned Uriah, "Haven't you just come from a journey? Why didn't you go home?"
102Sm 11:11 Uriah answered David, "The ark, Israel, and Judah are dwelling in tents, and my master Joab and his soldiers are camping in the open field. How can I enter my house to eat and drink and sleep with my wife? As surely as you live and by your life, I will not do this!"
102Sm 11:12 "Stay here today also," David said to Uriah, "and tomorrow I will send you back." So Uriah stayed in Jerusalem that day and the next.
102Sm 11:13 Then David invited Uriah to eat and drink with him, and David got him drunk. He went out in the evening to lie down on his cot with his master's servants, but he did not go home.
102Sm 11:14 The next morning David wrote a letter to Joab and sent it with Uriah.
102Sm 11:15 In the letter he wrote: Put Uriah at the front of the fiercest fighting, then withdraw from him so that he is struck down and dies.
102Sm 11:16 When Joab was besieging the city, he put Uriah in the place where he knew the best [enemy] soldiers were.
102Sm 11:17 Then the men of the city came out and attacked Joab, and some of the men from David's soldiers fell [in battle]; Uriah the Hittite also died.
102Sm 11:18 Joab sent someone to report to David all the details of the battle.
102Sm 11:19 He commanded the messenger, "When you've finished telling the king all the details of the battle--
102Sm 11:20 if the king's anger gets stirred up and he asks you, 'Why did you get so close to the city to fight? Didn't you realize they would shoot from the top of the wall?
102Sm 11:21 At Thebez, who struck Abimelech son of Jerubbesheth?Didn't a woman drop an upper millstone on him from the top of the wall so that he died? Why did you get so close to the wall?'-- then say, 'Your servant Uriah the Hittite is dead also.'"
102Sm 11:22 Then the messenger left. When he arrived, he reported to David all that Joab had sent him [to tell].
102Sm 11:23 The messenger reported to David, "The men gained the advantage over us and came out against us in the field, but we counterattacked right up to the entrance of the gate.
102Sm 11:24 However, the archers shot down on your soldiers from the top of the wall, and some of the king's soldiers died. Your servant Uriah the Hittite is also dead."
102Sm 11:25 David told the messenger, "Say this to Joab: 'Don't let this matter upset you because the sword devours all alike. Intensify your fight against the city and demolish it.' Encourage him."
102Sm 11:26 When Uriah's wife heard that her husband Uriah had died, she mourned for him.
102Sm 11:27 When the time of mourning ended, David had her brought to his house. She became his wife and bore him a son. However, the LORD considered what David had done to be evil.
102Sm 12:1 So the LORD sent Nathan to David. When he arrived, he said to him: There were two men in a certain city, one rich and the other poor.
102Sm 12:2 The rich man had a large number of sheep and cattle,
102Sm 12:3 but the poor man had nothing except one small ewe lamb that he had bought. It lived and grew up with him and his children. It shared his meager food and drank from his cup; it slept in his arms, and it was like a daughter to him.
102Sm 12:4 Now a traveler came to the rich man, but the rich man could not bring himself to take one of his own sheep or cattle to prepare for the traveler who had come to him. Instead, he took the poor man's lamb and prepared it for his guest.
102Sm 12:5 David was infuriated with the man and said to Nathan: "As surely as the LORD lives, the man who did this deserves to die!
102Sm 12:6 Because he has done this thing and shown no pity, he must pay four lambs for that lamb."
102Sm 12:7 Nathan replied to David, "You are the man! This is what the LORD God of Israel says: 'I anointed you king over Israel, and I delivered you from the hand of Saul.
102Sm 12:8 I gave your master's house to you and your master's wives into your arms, and I gave you the house of Israel and Judah, and if that was not enough, I would have given you even more.
102Sm 12:9 Why then have you despised the command of the LORD by doing what I consider evil? You struck down Uriah the Hittite with the sword and took his wife as your own wife-- you murdered him with the Ammonite's sword.
102Sm 12:10 Now therefore, the sword will never leave your house because you despised Me and took the wife of Uriah the Hittite to be your own wife.'
102Sm 12:11 "This is what the LORD says, 'I am going to bring disaster on you from your own family: I will take your wives and give them to another before your very eyes, and he will sleep with them publicly.
102Sm 12:12 You acted in secret, but I will do this before all Israel and in broad daylight.'"
102Sm 12:13 David responded to Nathan, "I have sinned against the LORD." Then Nathan replied to David, "The LORD has taken away your sin; you will not die.
102Sm 12:14 However, because you treated the LORD with such contempt in this matter, the son born to you will die."
102Sm 12:15 Then Nathan went home. The LORD struck the baby that Uriah's wife had borne to David, and he became ill.
102Sm 12:16 David pleaded with God for the boy. He fasted, went [home], and spent the night lying on the ground.
102Sm 12:17 The elders of his house stood beside him to get him up from the ground, but he was unwilling and would not eat anything with them.
102Sm 12:18 On the seventh day the baby died. But David's servants were afraid to tell him the baby was dead. They said, "Look, while the baby was alive, we spoke to him, and he wouldn't listen to us. So how can we tell him the baby is dead? He may do something desperate."
102Sm 12:19 When David saw that his servants were whispering to each other, he guessed that the baby was dead. So he asked his servants, "Is the baby dead?" "He is dead," they replied.
102Sm 12:20 Then David got up from the ground. He washed, anointed himself, changed his clothes, went to the LORD's house, and worshiped. Then he went home and requested [something to eat]. So they served him food, and he ate.
102Sm 12:21 His servants asked him, "What did you just do? While the baby was alive, you fasted and wept, but when he died, you got up and ate food."
102Sm 12:22 He answered, "While the baby was alive, I fasted and wept because I thought, 'Who knows? The LORD may be gracious to me and let him live.'
102Sm 12:23 But now that he is dead, why should I fast? Can I bring him back again? I'll go to him, but he will never return to me."
102Sm 12:24 Then David comforted his wife Bathsheba; he went and slept with her. She gave birth to a son and named him Solomon.The LORD loved him,
102Sm 12:25 and He sent [a message] through Nathan the prophet, who named him Jedidiah, because of the LORD.
102Sm 12:26 Joab fought against Rabbah of the Ammonites and captured the royal fortress.
102Sm 12:27 Then Joab sent messengers to David to say, "I have fought against Rabbah and have also captured the water supply.
102Sm 12:28 Now therefore, assemble the rest of the troops, lay siege to the city, and capture it. Otherwise I will be the one to capture the city, and it will be named after me.
102Sm 12:29 So David assembled all the troops and went to Rabbah; he fought against it and captured it.
102Sm 12:30 He took the crown from the head of their king, and it was [placed] on David's head. The crown weighed 75 pounds of gold, and it had a precious stone [in it]. In addition, David took away a large quantity of plunder from the city.
102Sm 12:31 He removed the people who were in the city and put [them to work] with saws, iron picks, and iron axes, and to labor at brickmaking. He did the same to all the Ammonite cities. Then he and all his troops returned to Jerusalem.
102Sm 13:1 Some time passed. David's son Absalom had a beautiful sister named Tamar, and David's son Amnon was infatuated with her.
102Sm 13:2 Amnon was frustrated to the point of making himself sick over his sister Tamar because she was a virgin, but it seemed impossible to do anything to her.
102Sm 13:3 Amnon had a friend named Jonadab, a son of David's brother Shimeah. Jonadab was a very shrewd man,
102Sm 13:4 and he asked Amnon, "Why are you, the king's son, so miserable every morning? Won't you tell me?" Amnon replied, "I'm in love with Tamar, my brother Absalom's sister."
102Sm 13:5 Jonadab said to him, "Lie down on your bed and pretend you're sick. When your father comes to see you, say to him, 'Please let my sister Tamar come and give me [something] to eat. Let her prepare food in my presence so I can watch and eat from her hand.'"
102Sm 13:6 So Amnon lay down and pretended to be sick. When the king came to see him, Amnon said to him, "Please let my sister Tamar come and make a couple of cakes in my presence so I can eat from her hand."
102Sm 13:7 David sent word to Tamar at the palace: "Please go to your brother Amnon's house and prepare a meal for him."
102Sm 13:8 Then Tamar went to his house while Amnon was lying down. She took dough, kneaded it, made cakes in his presence, and baked them.
102Sm 13:9 She brought the pan and set it down in front of him, but he refused to eat. Amnon said, "Everyone leave me!" And everyone left him.
102Sm 13:10 "Bring the meal to the bedroom," Amnon told Tamar, "so I can eat from your hand." Tamar took the cakes she had made and went to her brother Amnon's bedroom.
102Sm 13:11 When she brought [them] to him to eat, he grabbed her and said, "Come sleep with me, my sister!"
102Sm 13:12 "Don't, my brother!" she cried. "Don't humiliate me, for such a thing should never be done in Israel. Don't do this horrible thing!
102Sm 13:13 Where could I ever go with my disgrace? And you-- you would be like one of the immoral men in Israel! Please, speak to the king, for he won't keep me from you."
102Sm 13:14 But he refused to listen to her, and because he was stronger than she was, he raped her.
102Sm 13:15 After this, Amnon hated Tamar with such intensity that the hatred he hated her with was greater than the love he had loved her with. "Get out of here!" he said.
102Sm 13:16 "No," she cried, "sending me away is much worse than the great wrong you've already done to me!" But he refused to listen to her.
102Sm 13:17 Instead, he called to the servant who waited on him: "Throw this woman out and bolt the door behind her!"
102Sm 13:18 Amnon's servant threw her out and bolted the door behind her. Now Tamar was wearing a long-sleeved garment, because this is what the king's virgin daughters wore.
102Sm 13:19 Tamar put ashes on her head and tore the long-sleeved garment she was wearing. She put her hand on her head and went away weeping.
102Sm 13:20 Her brother Absalom said to her: "Has your brother Amnon been with you? Be quiet for now, my sister. He is your brother. Don't take this thing to heart." So Tamar lived as a desolate woman in the house of her brother Absalom.
102Sm 13:21 When King David heard about all these things, he was furious.
102Sm 13:22 Absalom didn't say anything to Amnon, either good or bad, because he hated Amnon since he disgraced his sister Tamar.
102Sm 13:23 Two years later, Absalom's sheepshearers were at Baal-hazor near Ephraim, and Absalom invited all the king's sons.
102Sm 13:24 Then he went to the king and said, "Your servant has just hired sheepshearers. Will the king and his servants please come with your servant?"
102Sm 13:25 The king replied to Absalom, "No, my son, we should not all go, or we would be a burden to you." Although Absalom urged him, he wasn't willing to go, though he did bless him.
102Sm 13:26 "If not," Absalom said, "please let my brother Amnon go with us." The king asked him, "Why should he go with you?"
102Sm 13:27 But Absalom urged him, so he sent Amnon and all the king's sons.
102Sm 13:28 Now Absalom commanded his young men, "Watch Amnon until he is in a good mood from the wine. When I order you to strike Amnon, then kill him. Don't be afraid. Am I not the one who has commanded you? Be strong and courageous!"
102Sm 13:29 So Absalom's young men did to Amnon just as Absalom had commanded. Then all [the rest of] the king's sons got up, and each fled on his mule.
102Sm 13:30 While they were on the way, a report reached David: "Absalom struck down all the king's sons; not even one of them survived!"
102Sm 13:31 In response the king stood up, tore his clothes, and lay down on the ground, and all his servants stood by with their clothes torn.
102Sm 13:32 But Jonadab, son of David's brother Shimeah, spoke up: "My lord must not think they have killed all the young men, the king's sons, because only Amnon is dead. In fact, Absalom has planned this ever since the day Amnon disgraced his sister Tamar.
102Sm 13:33 So now, my lord the king, don't take seriously the report that says all the king's sons are dead. Only Amnon is dead."
102Sm 13:34 Meanwhile, Absalom had fled. When the young man who was standing watch looked up, there were many people coming from the road west of him from the side of the mountain.
102Sm 13:35 Jonadab said to the king, "Look, the king's sons have come! It's exactly like your servant said."
102Sm 13:36 Just as he finished speaking, the king's sons entered and wept loudly. Then the king and all his servants also wept bitterly.
102Sm 13:37 Now Absalom fled and went to Talmai son of Ammihud, king of Geshur. And David mourned for his son every day.
102Sm 13:38 Absalom had fled and gone to Geshur where he stayed three years.
102Sm 13:39 Then King David longed to go to Absalom, for David had finished grieving over Amnon's death.
102Sm 14:1 Joab son of Zeruiah observed that the king's mind was on Absalom.
102Sm 14:2 So Joab sent someone to Tekoa to bring a clever woman from there. He told her, "Pretend to be in mourning: dress in mourning clothes and don't put on any oil. Act like a woman who has been mourning for the dead for a long time.
102Sm 14:3 Go to the king and speak these words to him." Then Joab told her exactly what to say.
102Sm 14:4 When the woman from Tekoa came to the king, she fell with her face to the ground in homage and said, "Help me, my king!"
102Sm 14:5 "What's the matter?" the king asked her. "To tell the truth, I am a widow; my husband died," she said.
102Sm 14:6 "Your servant had two sons. They were fighting in the field with no one to separate them, and one struck the other and killed him.
102Sm 14:7 Now the whole clan has risen up against your servant and said, 'Hand over the one who killed his brother so we may put him to death for the life of the brother he murdered. We will destroy the heir!' They would extinguish my one remaining ember by not preserving my husband's name or posterity on earth."
102Sm 14:8 The king told the woman, "Go home. I will issue a command on your behalf."
102Sm 14:9 Then the woman of Tekoa said to the king, "My lord the king, may any blame be on me and my father's house, and may the king and his throne be innocent."
102Sm 14:10 "Whoever speaks to you," the king said, "bring him to me. He will not trouble you again!"
102Sm 14:11 She replied, "Please, may the king invoke the LORD your God, so that the avenger of blood will not increase the loss, and they will not eliminate my son!" "As the LORD lives," he vowed, "not a hair of your son will fall to the ground."
102Sm 14:12 Then the woman said, "Please, may your servant speak a word to my lord the king?" "Speak," he replied.
102Sm 14:13 The woman asked, "Why have you devised something similar against the people of God? When the king spoke as he did about this matter, he has pronounced his own guilt. The king has not brought back his own banished one.
102Sm 14:14 For we will certainly die and be like water poured out on the ground, which can't be recovered. But God would not take away a life; He would devise plans so that the one banished from Him does not remain banished.
102Sm 14:15 "Now therefore, I've come to present this matter to my lord the king because the people have made me afraid. Your servant thought: I must speak to the king. Perhaps the king will grant his servant's request.
102Sm 14:16 The king will surely listen in order to rescue his servant from the hand of this man who would eliminate both me and my son from God's inheritance.
102Sm 14:17 Your servant thought: May the word of my lord the king bring relief, for my lord the king is able to discern the good and the bad like the Angel of God. May the LORD your God be with you."
102Sm 14:18 Then the king answered the woman, "I'm going to ask you something; don't conceal it from me!" "Let my lord the king speak," the woman replied.
102Sm 14:19 The king asked, "Did Joab put you up to all this?" The woman answered. "As surely as you live, my lord the king, no one can turn to the right or left from all my lord the king says. Yes, your servant Joab is the one who gave orders to me; he told your servant exactly what to say.
102Sm 14:20 Joab your servant has done this to address the issue indirectly, but my lord has wisdom like the wisdom of the Angel of God, knowing everything on earth."
102Sm 14:21 Then the king said to Joab, "I hereby grant this request. Go, bring back the young man Absalom."
102Sm 14:22 Joab fell with his face to the ground in homage and praised the king. "Today," Joab said, "your servant knows I have found favor with you, my lord the king, because the king has granted the request of your servant."
102Sm 14:23 So Joab got up, went to Geshur, and brought Absalom to Jerusalem.
102Sm 14:24 However, the king added, "He may return to his house, but he may not see my face." So Absalom returned to his house, but he did not see the king.
102Sm 14:25 No man in all Israel was as handsome and highly praised as Absalom. From the sole of his foot to the top of his head, he did not have a single flaw.
102Sm 14:26 When he shaved his head-- he shaved [it] every year because [his hair] got so heavy for him that he had to shave it off-- he would weigh the hair from his head and it would be five pounds according to the royal standard.
102Sm 14:27 Three sons were born to Absalom, and a daughter named Tamar, who was a beautiful woman.
102Sm 14:28 Absalom resided in Jerusalem two years but never saw the king.
102Sm 14:29 Then Absalom sent for Joab in order to send him to the king, but Joab was unwilling to come. So he sent again, a second time, but he still wouldn't come.
102Sm 14:30 Then Absalom said to his servants, "See, Joab has a field right next to mine, and he has barley there. Go and set fire to it!" So Absalom's servants set the field on fire.
102Sm 14:31 Then Joab came to Absalom's house and demanded, "Why did your servants set my field on fire?"
102Sm 14:32 "Look," Absalom explained to Joab, "I sent for you and said, 'Come here. I want to send you to the king to ask: Why have I come back from Geshur? I'd be better off if I were still there.' So now, let me see the king. If I am guilty, let him kill me."
102Sm 14:33 Joab went to the king and told him. So David summoned Absalom, who came to the king and bowed down with his face to the ground before the king. Then the king kissed Absalom.
102Sm 15:1 After this, Absalom got himself a chariot, horses, and 50 men to run before him.
102Sm 15:2 He would get up early and stand beside the road leading to the city gate. Whenever anyone had a grievance to bring before the king for settlement, Absalom called out to him and asked, "What city are you from?" If he replied, "Your servant is from one of the tribes of Israel,"
102Sm 15:3 Absalom said to him, "Look, your claims are good and right, but the king does not have anyone to listen to you."
102Sm 15:4 He added, "If only someone would appoint me judge in the land. Then anyone who had a grievance or dispute could come to me, and I would make sure he received justice."
102Sm 15:5 When a person approached to bow down to him, Absalom reached out his hand, took hold of him, and kissed him.
102Sm 15:6 Absalom did this to all the Israelites who came to the king for a settlement. So Absalom stole the hearts of the men of Israel.
102Sm 15:7 When four years had passed, Absalom said to the king, "Please let me go to Hebron to fulfill a vow I made to the Lord.
102Sm 15:8 For your servant made a vow when I lived in Geshur of Aram, saying: If the LORD really brings me back to Jerusalem, I will worship the LORD in Hebron."
102Sm 15:9 "Go in peace," the king said to him. So he went to Hebron.
102Sm 15:10 Then Absalom sent messengers throughout the tribes of Israel with this message: "When you hear the sound of the ram's horn, you are to say, 'Absalom has become king in Hebron!'"
102Sm 15:11 Two hundred men from Jerusalem went with Absalom. They had been invited and were going innocently, for they knew nothing about the whole matter.
102Sm 15:12 While he was offering the sacrifices, Absalom sent for David's adviser Ahithophel the Gilonite, from his city of Giloh. So the conspiracy grew strong, and the people supporting Absalom continued to increase.
102Sm 15:13 Then an informer came to David and reported, "The hearts of the men of Israel are with Absalom."
102Sm 15:14 David said to all the servants with him in Jerusalem, "Get up. We have to flee, or we will not escape from Absalom! Leave quickly, or he will overtake us, heap disaster on us, and strike the city with the edge of the sword."
102Sm 15:15 The king's servants said to him, "Whatever my lord the king decides, we are your servants."
102Sm 15:16 Then the king set out, and his entire household followed him. But he left behind 10 concubines to take care of the palace.
102Sm 15:17 So the king set out, and all the people followed him. They stopped at the last house
102Sm 15:18 while all his servants marched past him. Then all the Cherethites, the Pelethites, and the Gittites-- 600 men who came with him from Gath-- marched past the king.
102Sm 15:19 The king said to Ittai the Gittite, "Why are you also going with us? Go back and stay with the king since you're both a foreigner and an exile from your homeland.
102Sm 15:20 Besides, you only arrived yesterday; should I make you wander around with us today while I go wherever I can? Go back and take your brothers with you. May the LORD show you kindness and faithfulness."
102Sm 15:21 But in response, Ittai vowed to the king, "As surely as the LORD lives and as my lord the king lives, wherever my lord the king is, whether it means life or death, your servant will be there!"
102Sm 15:22 "March on," David replied to Ittai. So Ittai the Gittite marched past with all his men and the children who were with him.
102Sm 15:23 Everyone in the countryside was weeping loudly while all the people were marching past. As the king was crossing the Kidron Valley, all the people were marching past on the road that leads to the desert.
102Sm 15:24 Zadok was also there, and all the Levites with him were carrying the ark of the covenant of God. They set the ark of God down, and Abiathar offered [sacrifices] until the people had finished marching past.
102Sm 15:25 Then the king instructed Zadok, "Return the ark of God to the city. If I find favor in the LORD's eyes, He will bring me back and allow me to see both it and its dwelling place.
102Sm 15:26 However, if He should say, 'I do not delight in you,' then here I am-- He can do with me whatever pleases Him."
102Sm 15:27 The king also said to Zadok the priest, "Look, return to the city in peace and your two sons with you: your son Ahimaaz and Abiathar's son Jonathan.
102Sm 15:28 Remember, I'll wait at the fords of the wilderness until word comes from you to inform me."
102Sm 15:29 So Zadok and Abiathar returned the ark of God to Jerusalem and stayed there.
102Sm 15:30 David was climbing the slope of the Mount of Olives, weeping as he ascended. His head was covered, and he was walking barefoot. Each of the people with him covered their heads and went up, weeping as they ascended.
102Sm 15:31 Then someone reported to David: "Ahithophel is among the conspirators with Absalom." "LORD," David pleaded, "please turn the counsel of Ahithophel into foolishness!"
102Sm 15:32 When David came to the summit where he used to worship God, there to meet him was Hushai the Archite with his robe torn and dust on his head.
102Sm 15:33 David said to him, "If you go away with me, you'll be a burden to me,
102Sm 15:34 but if you return to the city and tell Absalom, 'I will be your servant, my king! Previously, I was your father's servant, but now I will be your servant,' then you can counteract Ahithophel's counsel for me.
102Sm 15:35 Won't Zadok and Abiathar the priests be there with you? Report everything you hear from the king's palace to Zadok and Abiathar the priests.
102Sm 15:36 Take note: their two sons, Zadok's son Ahimaaz and Abiathar's son Jonathan, are there with them. Send me everything you hear through them."
102Sm 15:37 So Hushai, David's personal adviser, entered Jerusalem just as Absalom was entering the city.
102Sm 16:1 When David had gone a little beyond the summit, Ziba, Mephibosheth's servant, was right there to meet him. He had a pair of saddled donkeys loaded with 200 loaves of bread, 100 clusters of raisins, 100 [bunches] of summer fruit, and a skin of wine.
102Sm 16:2 The king said to Ziba, "Why do you have these?" Ziba answered, "The donkeys are for the king's household to ride, the bread and summer fruit are for the young men to eat, and the wine is for those who become exhausted to drink in the desert."
102Sm 16:3 "Where is your master's son?" the king asked. "Why, he's staying in Jerusalem," Ziba replied to the king, "for he said, 'Today, the house of Israel will restore my father's kingdom to me.'"
102Sm 16:4 The king said to Ziba, "All that belongs to Mephibosheth is now yours!" "I bow [before you]," Ziba said. "May you look favorably on me, my lord the king!"
102Sm 16:5 When King David got to Bahurim, a man belonging to the family of the house of Saul was just coming out. His name was Shimei son of Gera, and he was yelling curses as he approached.
102Sm 16:6 He threw stones at David and at all the royal servants, the people and the warriors on David's right and left.
102Sm 16:7 Shimei said as he cursed: "Get out, get out, you worthless murderer!
102Sm 16:8 The LORD has paid you back for all the blood of the house of Saul in whose place you rule, and the LORD has handed the kingdom over to your son Absalom. Look, you are in trouble because you're a murderer!"
102Sm 16:9 Then Abishai son of Zeruiah said to the king, "Why should this dead dog curse my lord the king? Let me go over and cut his head off!"
102Sm 16:10 The king replied, "Sons of Zeruiah, do we agree on anything? He curses [me] this way because the LORD told him, 'Curse David!' Therefore, who can say, 'Why did you do that?'"
102Sm 16:11 Then David said to Abishai and all his servants, "Look, my own son, my own flesh and blood, intends to take my life-- how much more now this Benjaminite! Leave him alone and let him curse [me]; the LORD has told him to.
102Sm 16:12 Perhaps the LORD will see my affliction and restore goodness to me instead of Shimei's curses today."
102Sm 16:13 So David and his men proceeded along the road as Shimei was going along the ridge of the hill opposite him. As Shimei went, he cursed [David], and threw stones and dirt at him.
102Sm 16:14 Finally, the king and all the people with him arrived exhausted, so they rested there.
102Sm 16:15 Now Absalom and all the Israelites came to Jerusalem. Ahithophel was also with him.
102Sm 16:16 When David's friend Hushai the Archite came to Absalom, Hushai said to Absalom, "Long live the king! Long live the king!"
102Sm 16:17 "Is this your loyalty to your friend?" Absalom asked Hushai. "Why didn't you go with your friend?"
102Sm 16:18 "Not at all," Hushai answered Absalom. "I am on the side of the one that the LORD, the people, and all the men of Israel have chosen. I will stay with him.
102Sm 16:19 Furthermore, whom will I serve if not his son? As I served in your father's presence, I will also serve in yours."
102Sm 16:20 Then Absalom said to Ahithophel, "Give [me] your advice. What should we do?"
102Sm 16:21 Ahithophel replied to Absalom, "Sleep with your father's concubines he left to take care of the palace. When all Israel hears that you have become repulsive to your father, everyone with you will be encouraged."
102Sm 16:22 So they pitched a tent for Absalom on the roof, and he slept with his father's concubines in the sight of all Israel.
102Sm 16:23 Now the advice Ahithophel gave in those days was like someone asking about a word from God-- such was the regard that both David and Absalom had for Ahithophel's advice.
102Sm 17:1 Ahithophel said to Absalom, "Let me choose 12,000 men, and I will set out in pursuit of David tonight.
102Sm 17:2 I will attack him while he is weak and weary, throw him into a panic, and all the people with him will scatter. I will strike down only the king
102Sm 17:3 and bring all the people back to you. When everyone returns [except] the man you're seeking, all the people will be at peace."
102Sm 17:4 This proposal seemed good to Absalom and all the elders of Israel.
102Sm 17:5 Then Absalom said, "Summon Hushai the Archite also. Let's hear what he has to say as well."
102Sm 17:6 So Hushai came to Absalom, and Absalom told him: "Ahithophel offered this proposal. Should we carry out his proposal? If not, what do you say?"
102Sm 17:7 Hushai replied to Absalom, "The advice Ahithophel has given this time is not good."
102Sm 17:8 Hushai continued, "You know your father and his men. They are warriors and are desperate like a wild bear robbed of her cubs. Your father is an experienced soldier who won't spend the night with the people.
102Sm 17:9 He's probably already hiding in one of the caves or some other place. If some of our troops fall first, someone is sure to hear and say, 'There's been a slaughter among the people who follow Absalom.'
102Sm 17:10 Then, even a brave man with the heart of a lion will melt because all Israel knows that your father and the valiant men with him are warriors.
102Sm 17:11 Instead, I advise that all Israel from Dan to Beer-sheba-- as numerous as the sand by the sea-- be gathered to you and that you personally go into battle.
102Sm 17:12 Then we will attack David wherever we find him, and we will descend on him like dew on the ground. Not even one will be left of all the men with him.
102Sm 17:13 If he retreats to some city, all Israel will bring ropes to that city, and we will drag its [stones] into the valley until not even a pebble can be found there."
102Sm 17:14 Since the LORD had decreed that Ahithophel's good advice be undermined in order to bring about Absalom's ruin, Absalom and all the men of Israel said, "The advice of Hushai the Archite is better than Ahithophel's advice."
102Sm 17:15 Hushai then told the priests Zadok and Abiathar, "This is what Ahithophel advised Absalom and the elders of Israel, and this is what I advised.
102Sm 17:16 Now send someone quickly and tell David, 'Don't spend the night at the wilderness ford [of the Jordan], but be sure to cross over, or the king and all the people with him will be destroyed.'"
102Sm 17:17 Jonathan and Ahimaaz were staying at En-rogel, where a servant girl would come and pass along information to them. They in turn would go and inform King David, because they dared not be seen entering the city.
102Sm 17:18 However, a young man did see them and informed Absalom. So the two left quickly and came to the house of a man in Bahurim. He had a well in his courtyard, and they climbed down into it.
102Sm 17:19 Then his wife took the cover, placed it over the mouth of the well, and scattered grain on it so nobody would know anything.
102Sm 17:20 Absalom's servants came to the woman at the house and asked, "Where are Ahimaaz and Jonathan?" "They passed by toward the water," the woman replied to them. The men searched but did not find [them], so they returned to Jerusalem.
102Sm 17:21 After they had gone, Ahimaaz and Jonathan climbed out of the well and went and informed King David. They told him, "Get up and immediately ford the river, for Ahithophel has given this advice against you."
102Sm 17:22 So David and all the people with him got up and crossed the Jordan. By daybreak, there was no one who had not crossed the Jordan.
102Sm 17:23 When Ahithophel realized that his advice had not been followed, he saddled his donkey and set out for his house in his hometown. He set his affairs in order and hanged himself. So he died and was buried in his father's tomb.
102Sm 17:24 David had arrived at Mahanaim by the time Absalom crossed the Jordan with all the men of Israel.
102Sm 17:25 Now Absalom had appointed Amasa over the army in Joab's place. Amasa was the son of a man named Ithra the Israelite;Ithra had married Abigail daughter of Nahash. Abigail was a sister to Zeruiah, Joab's mother.
102Sm 17:26 And Israel and Absalom camped in the land of Gilead.
102Sm 17:27 When David came to Mahanaim, Shobi son of Nahash from Rabbah of the Ammonites, Machir son of Ammiel from Lo-debar, and Barzillai the Gileadite from Rogelim
102Sm 17:28 brought beds, basins, and pottery items. [They also brought] wheat, barley, flour, roasted grain, beans, lentils,
102Sm 17:29 honey, curds, sheep, and cheese from the herd for David and the people with him to eat. They had reasoned, "The people must be hungry, exhausted, and thirsty in the desert."
102Sm 18:1 David reviewed his troops and appointed commanders of hundreds and of thousands over them.
102Sm 18:2 He then sent out the troops, one third under Joab, one third under Joab's brother Abishai son of Zeruiah, and one third under Ittai the Gittite. The king said to the troops, "I will also march out with you."
102Sm 18:3 "You must not go!" the people pleaded. "If we have to flee, they will not pay any attention to us. Even if half of us die, they will not pay any attention to us because you are worth 10,000 of us. Therefore, it is better if you support us from the city."
102Sm 18:4 "I will do whatever you think is best," the king replied to them. So he stood beside the gate while all the troops marched out by hundreds and thousands.
102Sm 18:5 The king commanded Joab, Abishai, and Ittai, "Treat the young man Absalom gently for my sake." All the people heard the king's orders to all the commanders about Absalom.
102Sm 18:6 Then David's forces marched into the field to engage Israel in battle, which took place in the forest of Ephraim.
102Sm 18:7 The people of Israel were defeated by David's soldiers, and the slaughter there was vast that day-- 20,000 [casualties].
102Sm 18:8 The battle spread over the entire region, and that day the forest claimed more people than the sword.
102Sm 18:9 Absalom was riding on his mule when he happened to meet David's soldiers. When the mule went under the tangled branches of a large oak tree, Absalom's head was caught fast in the tree. The mule under him kept going, so he was suspended in midair.
102Sm 18:10 One of the men saw [him] and informed Joab. He said, "I just saw Absalom hanging in an oak tree!"
102Sm 18:11 "You just saw [him]!" Joab exclaimed. "Why didn't you strike him to the ground right there? I would have given you 10 silver pieces and a belt!"
102Sm 18:12 The man replied to Joab, "Even if I had the weight of 1,000 pieces of silver in my hand, I would not raise my hand against the king's son. For we heard the king command you, Abishai, and Ittai, 'Protect the young man Absalom for me.'
102Sm 18:13 If I had jeopardized my own life-- and nothing is hidden from the king-- you would have abandoned me."
102Sm 18:14 Joab said, "I'm not going to waste time with you!" He then took three spears in his hand and thrust them into Absalom's heart while he was still alive in the oak tree,
102Sm 18:15 and 10 young men who were Joab's armor-bearers surrounded Absalom, struck him, and killed him.
102Sm 18:16 Afterwards, Joab blew the ram's horn, and the troops broke off their pursuit of Israel because Joab restrained them.
102Sm 18:17 They took Absalom, threw him into a large pit in the forest, and piled a huge mound of stones over him. And all Israel fled, each to his tent.
102Sm 18:18 When he was alive, Absalom had erected for himself a pillar in the King's Valley, for he had said, "I have no son to preserve the memory of my name." So he gave the pillar his name. It is still called Absalom's Monument today.
102Sm 18:19 Ahimaaz son of Zadok said, "Please let me run and tell the king the good news that the LORD has delivered him from his enemies."
102Sm 18:20 Joab replied to him, "You are not the man to take good news today. You may do it another day, but today you aren't taking good news, because the king's son is dead."
102Sm 18:21 Joab then said to the Cushite, "Go tell the king what you have seen." The Cushite bowed to Joab and took off running.
102Sm 18:22 However, Ahimaaz son of Zadok persisted and said to Joab, "No matter what, please let me run too behind the Cushite!" Joab replied, "My son, why do you want to run since you won't get a reward?"
102Sm 18:23 "No matter what I want to run!" "Then run!" Joab said to him. So Ahimaaz ran by way of the plain and outran the Cushite.
102Sm 18:24 David was sitting between the two gates when the watchman went up to the roof of the gate and over to the wall. The watchman looked out and saw a man running alone.
102Sm 18:25 He called out and told the king. The king said, "If he's alone, he bears good news." As the first runner came closer,
102Sm 18:26 the watchman saw another man running. He called out to the gatekeeper, "Look! Another man is running alone!" "This one is also bringing good news," said the king.
102Sm 18:27 The watchman said, "The way the first man runs looks to me like the way Ahimaaz son of Zadok runs." "This is a good man; he comes with good news," the king commented.
102Sm 18:28 Ahimaaz called out to the king, "All is well," and then bowed down to the king with his face to the ground. He continued, "May the LORD your God be praised! He delivered up the men who rebelled against my lord the king."
102Sm 18:29 The king asked, "Is the young man Absalom all right?" Ahimaaz replied, "When Joab sent the king's servant and your servant, I saw a big disturbance, but I don't know what [it was]."
102Sm 18:30 The king said, "Move aside and stand here." So he stood to one side.
102Sm 18:31 Just then the Cushite came and said, "May my lord the king hear the good news: today the LORD has delivered you from all those rising up against you!"
102Sm 18:32 The king asked the Cushite, "Is the young man Absalom all right?" The Cushite replied, "May what has become of the young man happen to the enemies of my lord the king and to all who rise up against you with evil intent."
102Sm 18:33  The king was deeply moved and went up to the gate chamber and wept. As he walked, he cried, "My son Absalom! My son, my son Absalom! If only I had died instead of you, Absalom, my son, my son!"
102Sm 19:1 It was reported to Joab, "The king is weeping. He's mourning over Absalom."
102Sm 19:2 That day's victory was turned into mourning for all the troops because on that day the troops heard, "The king is grieving over his son."
102Sm 19:3 So they returned to the city quietly that day like people come in when they are humiliated after fleeing in battle.
102Sm 19:4 But the king hid his face and cried out at the top of his voice, "My son Absalom! Absalom, my son, my son!"
102Sm 19:5 Then Joab went into the house to the king and said, "Today you have shamed all your soldiers-- those who rescued your life and the lives of your sons and daughters, your wives, and your concubines.
102Sm 19:6 You love your enemies and hate those who love you! Today you have made it clear that the commanders and soldiers mean nothing to you. In fact, today I know that if Absalom were alive and all of us were dead, it would be fine with you!
102Sm 19:7 "Now get up! Go out and encourage your soldiers, for I swear by the LORD that if you don't go out, not a man will remain with you tonight. This will be worse for you than all the trouble that has come to you from your youth until now!"
102Sm 19:8 So the king got up and sat in the gate, and all the people were told: "Look, the king is sitting in the gate." Then they all came into the king's presence. Meanwhile, each Israelite had fled to his tent.
102Sm 19:9 All the people among all the tribes of Israel were arguing: "The king delivered us from the grasp of our enemies, and he rescued us from the grasp of the Philistines, but now he has fled from the land because of Absalom.
102Sm 19:10 But Absalom, the man we anointed over us, has died in battle. So why do you say nothing about restoring the king?"
102Sm 19:11 King David sent word to the priests, Zadok and Abiathar: "Say to the elders of Judah, 'Why should you be the last to restore the king to his palace? The talk of all Israel has reached the king at his house.
102Sm 19:12 You are my brothers, my flesh and blood. So why should you be the last to restore the king?'
102Sm 19:13 And tell Amasa, 'Aren't you my flesh and blood? May God punish me and do so severely if you don't become commander of the army from now on instead of Joab!'"
102Sm 19:14 So he won over all the men of Judah, and they sent word to the king: "Come back, you and all your servants."
102Sm 19:15 Then the king returned. When he arrived at the Jordan, Judah came to Gilgal to meet the king and escort him across the Jordan.
102Sm 19:16 Shimei son of Gera, a Benjaminite from Bahurim, hurried down with the men of Judah to meet King David.
102Sm 19:17 There were 1,000 men from Benjamin with him. Ziba, an attendant from the house of Saul, with his 15 sons and 20 servants also rushed down to the Jordan ahead of the king.
102Sm 19:18 They forded the Jordan to bring the king's household across and do whatever the king desired. When Shimei son of Gera crossed the Jordan, he fell down before the king
102Sm 19:19 and said to him, "My lord, don't hold me guilty, and don't remember your servant's wrongdoing on the day my lord the king left Jerusalem. May the king not take it to heart.
102Sm 19:20 For your servant knows that I have sinned. But look! Today I am the first one of the entire house of Joseph to come down to meet my lord the king."
102Sm 19:21 Abishai son of Zeruiah asked, "Shouldn't Shimei be put to death for this, because he ridiculed the LORD's anointed?"
102Sm 19:22 David answered, "Sons of Zeruiah, do we agree on anything? Have you become my adversary today? Should any man be killed in Israel today? Am I not aware that today I'm king over Israel?"
102Sm 19:23 So the king said to Shimei, "You will not die." Then the king gave him his oath.
102Sm 19:24 Mephibosheth, Saul's grandson, also went down to meet the king. He had not taken care of his feet, trimmed his moustache, or washed his clothes from the day the king left until the day he returned safely.
102Sm 19:25 When he came from Jerusalem to meet the king, the king asked him, "Mephibosheth, why didn't you come with me?"
102Sm 19:26 "My lord the king," he replied, "my servant [Ziba] betrayed me. Actually your servant said: 'I'll saddle the donkey for myself so that I may ride it and go with the king'-- for your servant is lame.
102Sm 19:27 Ziba slandered your servant to my lord the king. But my lord the king is like the Angel of God, so do whatever you think best.
102Sm 19:28 For my grandfather's entire family deserves death from my lord the king, but you set your servant among those who eat at your table. So what further right do I have to keep on making appeals to the king?"
102Sm 19:29 The king said to him, "Why keep on speaking about [these] matters of yours? I hereby declare: you and Ziba are to divide the land."
102Sm 19:30 Mephibosheth said to the king, "Instead, since my lord the king has come to his palace safely, let Ziba take it all!"
102Sm 19:31 Barzillai the Gileadite had come down from Rogelim and accompanied the king to the Jordan River to see him off at the Jordan.
102Sm 19:32 Barzillai was a very old man-- 80 years old-- and since he was a very wealthy man, he had provided for the needs of the king while he stayed in Mahanaim.
102Sm 19:33 The king said to Barzillai, "Cross over with me, and I'll provide for you at my side in Jerusalem."
102Sm 19:34 Barzillai replied to the king, "How many years of my life are left that I should go up to Jerusalem with the king?
102Sm 19:35 I'm now 80 years old. Can I discern what is pleasant and what is not? Can your servant taste what he eats or drinks? Can I still hear the voice of male and female singers? Why should your servant be an added burden to my lord the king?
102Sm 19:36 Since your servant is only going with the king a little way across the Jordan, why should the king repay me with such a reward?
102Sm 19:37 Please let your servant return so that I may die in my own city near the tomb of my father and mother. But here is your servant Chimham: let him cross over with my lord the king. Do for him what seems good to you."
102Sm 19:38 The king replied, "Chimham will cross over with me, and I will do for him what seems good to you, and whatever you desire from me I will do for you."
102Sm 19:39 So all the people crossed the Jordan, and then the king crossed. The king kissed Barzillai and blessed him, and Barzillai returned to his home.
102Sm 19:40 The king went on to Gilgal, and Chimham went with him. All the troops of Judah and half of Israel's escorted the king.
102Sm 19:41 Suddenly, all the men of Israel came to the king. They asked him, "Why did our brothers, the men of Judah, take you away secretly and transport the king and his household across the Jordan, along with all of David's men?"
102Sm 19:42 All the men of Judah responded to the men of Israel, "Because the king is our relative. Why does this make you angry? Have we ever eaten anything of the king's or been honored at all?"
102Sm 19:43 The men of Israel answered the men of Judah: "We have 10 shares in the king, so we have a greater [claim] to David than you. Why then do you despise us? Weren't we the first to speak of restoring our king?" But the words of the men of Judah were harsher than those of the men of Israel.
102Sm 20:1 Now a wicked man, a Benjaminite named Sheba son of Bichri, happened to be there. He blew the ram's horn and shouted: We have no portion in David, no inheritance in Jesse's son. Each man to his tent, Israel!
102Sm 20:2 So all the men of Israel deserted David and followed Sheba son of Bichri, but the men of Judah from the Jordan all the way to Jerusalem remained loyal to their king.
102Sm 20:3 When David came to his palace in Jerusalem, he took the 10 concubines he had left to take care of the palace and placed them under guard. He provided for them, but he was not intimate with them. They were confined until the day of their death, living as widows.
102Sm 20:4 The king said to Amasa, "Summon the men of Judah to me within three days and be here yourself."
102Sm 20:5 Amasa went to summon Judah, but he took longer than the time allotted him.
102Sm 20:6 So David said to Abishai, "Sheba son of Bichri will do more harm to us than Absalom. Take your lord's soldiers and pursue him, or he will find fortified cities and elude us."
102Sm 20:7 So Joab's men, the Cherethites, the Pelethites, and all the warriors marched out under Abishai's command; they left Jerusalem to pursue Sheba son of Bichri.
102Sm 20:8 They were at the great stone in Gibeon when Amasa joined them. Joab was wearing his uniform and over it was a belt around his waist with a sword in its sheath. As he approached, [the sword] fell out.
102Sm 20:9 Joab asked Amasa, "Are you well, my brother?" Then with his right hand Joab grabbed Amasa by the beard to kiss him.
102Sm 20:10 Amasa was not on guard against the sword in Joab's hand, and Joab stabbed him in the stomach with it and spilled his intestines out on the ground. Joab did not stab him again for Amasa was dead. Joab and his brother Abishai pursued Sheba son of Bichri.
102Sm 20:11 One of Joab's young men had stood over Amasa saying, "Whoever favors Joab and whoever is for David, follow Joab!"
102Sm 20:12 Now Amasa was writhing in his blood in the middle of the highway, and the man had seen that all the people stopped. So he moved Amasa from the highway to the field and threw a garment over him because he realized that all those who encountered Amasa were stopping.
102Sm 20:13 When he was removed from the highway, all the men passed by and followed Joab to pursue Sheba son of Bichri.
102Sm 20:14 Sheba passed through all the tribes of Israel to Abel of Beth-maacah. All the Berites came together and followed him.
102Sm 20:15 Joab's troops came and besieged Sheba in Abel of Beth-maacah. They built an assault ramp against the outer wall of the city. While all the troops with Joab were battering the wall to make it collapse,
102Sm 20:16 a wise woman called out from the city, "Listen! Listen! Please tell Joab to come here and let me speak with him."
102Sm 20:17 When he had come near her, the woman asked, "Are you Joab?" "I am," he replied. "Listen to the words of your servant," she said to him. He answered, "I'm listening."
102Sm 20:18 She said, "In the past they used to say, 'Seek counsel in Abel,' and that's how they settled [disputes].
102Sm 20:19 I am a peaceful person, one of the faithful in Israel, but you're trying to destroy a city that is like a mother in Israel. Why would you devour the LORD's inheritance?"
102Sm 20:20 Joab protested: "Never! I do not want to destroy!
102Sm 20:21 That is not [my] intention. There is a man named Sheba son of Bichri, from the hill country of Ephraim, who has rebelled against King David. Deliver this one man, and I will withdraw from the city." The woman replied to Joab, "All right. His head will be thrown over the wall to you."
102Sm 20:22 The woman went to all the people with her wise counsel, and they cut off the head of Sheba son of Bichri and threw it to Joab. So he blew the ram's horn, and they dispersed from the city, each to his own tent. Joab returned to the king in Jerusalem.
102Sm 20:23 Joab commanded the whole army of Israel; Benaiah son of Jehoiada was over the Cherethites and Pelethites;
102Sm 20:24 Adoram was in charge of forced labor; Jehoshaphat son of Ahilud was court historian;
102Sm 20:25 Sheva was court secretary; Zadok and Abiathar were priests;
102Sm 20:26 and in addition, Ira the Jairite was David's priest.
102Sm 21:1 During David's reign there was a famine for three successive years, so David inquired of the LORD. The LORD answered, "It is because of the blood shed by Saul and his family when he killed the Gibeonites."
102Sm 21:2 The Gibeonites were not Israelites but rather a remnant of the Amorites. The Israelites had taken an oath concerning them, but Saul had tried to kill them in his zeal for the Israelites and Judah. So David summoned the Gibeonites and spoke to them.
102Sm 21:3 He asked the Gibeonites, "What should I do for you? How can I wipe out this guilt so that you will bring a blessing on the LORD's inheritance?"
102Sm 21:4 The Gibeonites said to him, "We are not asking for money from Saul or his family, and we cannot put anyone to death in Israel." "Whatever you say, I will do for you," he said.
102Sm 21:5 They replied to the king, "As for the man who annihilated us and plotted to exterminate us so we would not exist within the whole territory of Israel,
102Sm 21:6 let seven of his male descendants be handed over to us so we may hang them in the presence of the LORD at Gibeah of Saul, the LORD's chosen." The king answered, "I will hand them over."
102Sm 21:7 David spared Mephibosheth, the son of Saul's son Jonathan, because of the oath of the LORD that was between David and Jonathan, Saul's son.
102Sm 21:8 But the king took Armoni and Mephibosheth, who were the two sons whom Rizpah daughter of Aiah had borne to Saul, and the five sons whom Merabdaughter of Saul had borne to Adriel son of Barzillai the Meholathite
102Sm 21:9 and handed them over to the Gibeonites. They hanged them on the hill in the presence of the LORD; the seven of them died together. They were executed in the first days of the harvest at the beginning of the barley harvest.
102Sm 21:10 Rizpah, Aiah's daughter, took sackcloth and spread it out for herself on the rock from the beginning of the harvest until the rain poured down from heaven on the bodies. She kept the birds of the sky from them by day and the wild animals by night.
102Sm 21:11 When it was reported to David what Saul's concubine Rizpah, daughter of Aiah, had done,
102Sm 21:12 he went and got the bones of Saul and his son Jonathan from the leaders of Jabesh-gilead. They had stolen them from the public square of Beth-shan where the Philistines had hung them the day the Philistines killed Saul at Gilboa.
102Sm 21:13 David had the bones brought from there. They also gathered up the bones of Saul's family who had been hung.
102Sm 21:14 They [also] buried the bones of Saul and his son Jonathan at Zela in the land of Benjamin in the tomb of Saul's father Kish. They did everything the king commanded. After this, God answered prayer for the land.
102Sm 21:15 The Philistines again waged war against Israel. David went down with his soldiers, and they fought the Philistines, but David became exhausted.
102Sm 21:16 Then Ishbi-benob, one of the descendants of the giant, whose bronze spear weighed about eight pounds and who wore new armor, intended to kill David.
102Sm 21:17 But Abishai son of Zeruiah came to his aid, struck the Philistine, and killed him. Then David's men swore to him: "You must never again go out with us to battle. You must not extinguish the lamp of Israel."
102Sm 21:18 After this, there was another battle with the Philistines at Gob. At that time Sibbecai the Hushathite killed Saph, who was one of the descendants of the giant.
102Sm 21:19 Once again there was a battle with the Philistines at Gob, and Elhanan son of Jaare-oregim the Bethlehemite killed Goliath the Gittite. The shaft of his spear was like a weaver's beam.
102Sm 21:20 At Gath there was still another battle. A huge man was there with six fingers on each hand and six toes on each foot-- 24 in all. He, too, was descended from the giant.
102Sm 21:21 When he taunted Israel, Jonathan, son of David's brother Shimei, killed him.
102Sm 21:22 These four were descended from the giant in Gath and were killed by David and his soldiers.
102Sm 22:1 David spoke the words of this song to the LORD on the day the LORD rescued him from the hand of all his enemies and from the hand of Saul.
102Sm 22:2 He said: The LORD is my rock, my fortress, and my deliverer,
102Sm 22:3 my God, my mountain where I seek refuge. My shield, the horn of my salvation, my stronghold, my refuge, and my Savior, You save me from violence.
102Sm 22:4 I called to the LORD, who is worthy of praise, and I was saved from my enemies.
102Sm 22:5 For the waves of death engulfed me; the torrents of destruction terrified me.
102Sm 22:6 The ropes of Sheol entangled me; the snares of death confronted me.
102Sm 22:7 I called to the LORD in my distress; I called to my God. From His temple He heard my voice, and my cry for help [reached] His ears.
102Sm 22:8 Then the earth shook and quaked; the foundations of the heavens trembled; they shook because He burned with anger.
102Sm 22:9 Smoke rose from His nostrils, and consuming fire [came] from His mouth; coals were set ablaze by it.
102Sm 22:10 He parted the heavens and came down, a dark cloud beneath His feet.
102Sm 22:11 He rode on a cherub and flew, soaring on the wings of the wind.
102Sm 22:12 He made darkness a canopy around Him, a gathering of water and thick clouds.
102Sm 22:13 From the radiance of His presence, flaming coals were ignited.
102Sm 22:14 The LORD thundered from heaven; the Most High projected His voice.
102Sm 22:15 He shot arrows and scattered them; [He hurled] lightning bolts and routed them.
102Sm 22:16 The depths of the sea became visible, the foundations of the world were exposed at the rebuke of the Lord, at the blast of the breath of His nostrils.
102Sm 22:17 He reached down from on high and took hold of me; He pulled me out of deep waters.
102Sm 22:18 He rescued me from my powerful enemy and from those who hated me, for they were too strong for me.
102Sm 22:19 They confronted me in the day of my distress, but the LORD was my support.
102Sm 22:20 He brought me out to a wide-open place; He rescued me because He delighted in me.
102Sm 22:21 The LORD rewarded me according to my righteousness; He repaid me according to the cleanness of my hands.
102Sm 22:22 For I have kept the ways of the LORD and have not turned from my God to wickedness.
102Sm 22:23 Indeed, I have kept all His ordinances in mind and have not disregarded His statutes.
102Sm 22:24 I was blameless before Him and kept myself from sinning.
102Sm 22:25 So the LORD repaid me according to my righteousness, according to my cleanness in His sight.
102Sm 22:26 With the faithful You prove Yourself faithful; with the blameless man You prove Yourself blameless;
102Sm 22:27 with the pure You prove Yourself pure, but with the crooked You prove Yourself shrewd.
102Sm 22:28 You rescue an afflicted people, but Your eyes are set against the proud-- You humble them.
102Sm 22:29 LORD, You are my lamp; the LORD illuminates my darkness.
102Sm 22:30 With You I can attack a barrier, and with my God I can leap over a wall.
102Sm 22:31 God-- His way is perfect; the word of the LORD is pure. He is a shield to all who take refuge in Him.
102Sm 22:32 For who is God besides the LORD? And who is a rock? Only our God.
102Sm 22:33 God is my strong refuge; He makes my way perfect.
102Sm 22:34 He makes my feet like [the feet of] a deer and sets me securely on the heights.
102Sm 22:35 He trains my hands for war; my arms can bend a bow of bronze.
102Sm 22:36 You have given me the shield of Your salvation; Your help exalts me.
102Sm 22:37 You widen [a place] beneath me for my steps, and my ankles do not give way.
102Sm 22:38 I pursue my enemies and destroy them; I do not turn back until they are wiped out.
102Sm 22:39 I wipe them out and crush them, and they do not rise; they fall beneath my feet.
102Sm 22:40 You have clothed me with strength for battle; You subdue my adversaries beneath me.
102Sm 22:41 You have made my enemies retreat before me; I annihilate those who hated me.
102Sm 22:42 They look, but there is no one to save [them]-- [they look] to the LORD, but He does not answer them.
102Sm 22:43 I pulverize them like dust of the earth; I crush them and trample them like mud in the streets.
102Sm 22:44 You have freed me from the feuds among my people; You have appointed me the head of nations; a people I had not known serve me.
102Sm 22:45 Foreigners submit to me grudgingly; as soon as they hear, they obey me.
102Sm 22:46 Foreigners lose heart and come trembling from their fortifications.
102Sm 22:47 The LORD lives-- may my rock be praised! God, the rock of my salvation, is exalted.
102Sm 22:48 God-- He gives me vengeance and casts down peoples under me.
102Sm 22:49 He frees me from my enemies. You exalt me above my adversaries; You rescue me from violent men.
102Sm 22:50 Therefore I will praise You, LORD, among the nations; I will sing about Your name.
102Sm 22:51 He is a tower of salvation for His king; He shows loyalty to His anointed, to David and his descendants forever.
102Sm 23:1 These are the last words of David: The proclamation of David son of Jesse, the proclamation of the man raised on high, the one anointed by the God of Jacob, the favorite singer of Israel:
102Sm 23:2 The Spirit of the LORD spoke through me, His word was on my tongue.
102Sm 23:3 The God of Israel spoke; the Rock of Israel said to me, "The one who rules the people with justice, who rules in the fear of God,
102Sm 23:4 is like the morning light when the sun rises on a cloudless morning, the glisten of rain on sprouting grass."
102Sm 23:5 Is it not true my house is with God? For He has established an everlasting covenant with me, ordered and secured in every [detail]. Will He not bring about my whole salvation and [my] every desire?
102Sm 23:6 But all the wicked are like thorns raked aside; they can never be picked up by hand.
102Sm 23:7 The man who touches them must be armed with iron and the shaft of a spear. They will be completely burned up on the spot.
102Sm 23:8 These are the names of David's warriors: Josheb-basshebeth the Tahchemonite was chief of the officers. He wielded his spear against 800 [men] he killed at one time.
102Sm 23:9 After him, Eleazar son of Dodo son of Ahohi was among the three warriors with David when they defied the Philistines. The men of Israel retreated in the place they had gathered for battle,
102Sm 23:10 but Eleazar stood [his ground] and attacked the Philistines until his hand was tired and stuck to his sword. The LORD brought about a great victory that day. Then the troops came back to him, but only to plunder the dead.
102Sm 23:11 After him was Shammah son of Agee the Hararite. The Philistines had assembled [in formation] where there was a field full of lentils. The troops fled from the Philistines,
102Sm 23:12 but Shammah took his stand in the middle of the field, defended it, and struck down the Philistines. So the LORD brought about a great victory.
102Sm 23:13 Three of the 30 leading [warriors] went down at harvest time and came to David at the cave of Adullam, while a company of Philistines was camping in the Valley of Rephaim.
102Sm 23:14 At that time David was in the stronghold, and a Philistine garrison was at Bethlehem.
102Sm 23:15 David was extremely thirsty and said, "If only someone would bring me water to drink from the well at the city gate of Bethlehem!"
102Sm 23:16 So three of the warriors broke through the Philistine camp and drew water from the well at the gate of Bethlehem. They brought it back to David, but he refused to drink it. Instead, he poured it out to the LORD.
102Sm 23:17 David said, "LORD, I would never do such a thing! Is this not the blood of men who risked their lives?" So he refused to drink it. Such were the exploits of the three warriors.
102Sm 23:18 Abishai, Joab's brother and son of Zeruiah, was leader of the Three. He raised his spear against 300 [men] and killed them, gaining a reputation among the Three.
102Sm 23:19 Was he not the most honored of the Three? He became their commander even though he did not become one of the Three.
102Sm 23:20 Benaiah son of Jehoiada was the son of a brave man from Kabzeel, a man of many exploits. Benaiah killed two sons of Ariel of Moab, and he went down into a pit on a snowy day and killed a lion.
102Sm 23:21 He also killed an Egyptian, a huge man. Even though the Egyptian had a spear in his hand, Benaiah went down to him with a club, snatched the spear out of the Egyptian's hand, and then killed him with his own spear.
102Sm 23:22 These were the exploits of Benaiah son of Jehoiada, who had a reputation among the three warriors.
102Sm 23:23 He was the most honored of the Thirty, but he did not become one of the Three. David put him in charge of his bodyguard.
102Sm 23:24 Among the Thirty were: Joab's brother Asahel, Elhanan son of Dodo of Bethlehem,
102Sm 23:25 Shammah the Harodite, Elika the Harodite,
102Sm 23:26 Helez the Paltite, Ira son of Ikkesh the Tekoite,
102Sm 23:27 Abiezer the Anathothite, Mebunnai the Hushathite,
102Sm 23:28 Zalmon the Ahohite, Maharai the Netophathite,
102Sm 23:29 Heleb son of Baanah the Netophahite, Ittai son of Ribai from Gibeah of the Benjaminites,
102Sm 23:30 Benaiah the Pirathonite, Hiddai from the Wadis of Gaash,
102Sm 23:31 Abi-albon the Arbathite, Azmaveth the Barhumite,
102Sm 23:32 Eliahba the Shaalbonite, the sons of Jashen, Jonathan son of
102Sm 23:33 Shammah the Hararite, Ahiam son of Sharar the Hararite,
102Sm 23:34 Eliphelet son of Ahasbai son of the Maacathite, Eliam son of Ahithophel the Gilonite,
102Sm 23:35 Hezro the Carmelite, Paarai the Arbite,
102Sm 23:36 Igal son of Nathan from Zobah, Bani the Gadite,
102Sm 23:37 Zelek the Ammonite, Naharai the Beerothite, the armor-bearer for Joab son of Zeruiah,
102Sm 23:38 Ira the Ithrite, Gareb the Ithrite,
102Sm 23:39 and Uriah the Hittite. There were 37 in all.
102Sm 24:1 The LORD's anger burned against Israel again, and it stirred up David against them to say: "Go, count [the people of] Israel and Judah."
102Sm 24:2 So the king said to Joab, the commander of his army, "Go through all the tribes of Israel from Dan to Beer-sheba and register the troops so I can know their number."
102Sm 24:3 Joab replied to the king, "May the LORD your God multiply the troops 100 times more than they are-- while my lord the king looks on! But why does my lord the king want to do this?"
102Sm 24:4 Yet the king's order prevailed over Joab and the commanders of the army. So Joab and the commanders of the army left the king's presence to register the troops of Israel.
102Sm 24:5 They crossed the Jordan and camped in Aroer, south of the town in the middle of the valley, and then [proceeded] toward Gad and Jazer.
102Sm 24:6 They went to Gilead and to the land of the Hittites and continued on to Dan-jaan and around to Sidon.
102Sm 24:7 They went to the fortress of Tyre and all the cities of the Hivites and Canaanites. Afterwards, they went to the Negev of Judah at Beer-sheba.
102Sm 24:8 When they had gone through the whole land, they returned to Jerusalem at the end of nine months and 20 days.
102Sm 24:9 Joab gave the king the total of the registration of the troops. There were 800,000 fighting men from Israel and 500,000 men from Judah.
102Sm 24:10 David's conscience troubled him after he had taken a census of the troops. He said to the LORD, "I have sinned greatly in what I've done. Now, Lord, because I've been very foolish, please take away your servant's guilt."
102Sm 24:11 When David got up in the morning, a revelation from the LORD had come to the prophet Gad, David's seer:
102Sm 24:12 "Go and say to David, 'This is what the LORD says: I am offering you three [choices]. Choose one of them, and I will do it to you.'"
102Sm 24:13 So Gad went to David, told him [the choices], and asked him, "Do you want three years of famine to come on your land, to flee from your foes three months while they pursue you, or to have a plague in your land three days? Now, think it over and decide what answer I should take back to the One who sent me."
102Sm 24:14 David answered Gad, "I have great anxiety. Please, let us fall into the LORD's hands because His mercies are great, but don't let me fall into human hands."
102Sm 24:15 So the LORD sent a plague on Israel from that morning until the appointed time, and from Dan to Beer-sheba 70,000 men died.
102Sm 24:16 Then the angel extended his hand toward Jerusalem to destroy it, but the LORD relented concerning the destruction and said to the angel who was destroying the people, "Enough, withdraw your hand now!" The angel of the LORD was then at the threshing floor of Araunah the Jebusite.
102Sm 24:17 When David saw the angel striking the people, he said to the LORD, "Look, I am the one who has sinned; I am the one who has done wrong. But these sheep, what have they done? Please, let Your hand be against me and my father's family."
102Sm 24:18 Gad came to David that day and said to him, "Go up and set up an altar to the LORD on the threshing floor of Araunah the Jebusite."
102Sm 24:19 David went up in obedience to Gad's command, just as the LORD had commanded.
102Sm 24:20 Araunah looked down and saw the king and his servants coming toward him, so he went out and bowed to the king with his face to the ground.
102Sm 24:21 Araunah said, "Why has my lord the king come to his servant?" David replied, "To buy the threshing floor from you in order to build an altar to the LORD, so the plague on the people may be halted."
102Sm 24:22 Araunah said to David, "My lord the king may take whatever he wants and offer it. Here are the oxen for a burnt offering and the threshing sledges and ox yokes for the wood.
102Sm 24:23 [My] king, Araunah gives everything here to the king." Then he said to the king, "May the LORD your God accept you."
102Sm 24:24 The king answered Araunah, "No, I insist on buying it from you for a price, for I will not offer to the LORD my God burnt offerings that cost [me] nothing." David bought the threshing floor and the oxen for 50 ounces of silver.
102Sm 24:25 He built an altar to the LORD there and offered burnt offerings and fellowship offerings. Then the LORD answered prayer on behalf of the land, and the plague on Israel ended.
